<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Firefighters declared a temporary victory Friday in their battle to keep a forest fire out of a small <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> town, and forest officials warned that more lightning and dry, hot weather were forecast this weekend. `` It's like sitting on a time bomb,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, recreation officer for the <ORGANIZATION> Sawtooth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recreation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> in central <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. `` If we can get through this weekend without a conflagration, it will be a miracle.'' Forests and rangeland burned Friday in parts of <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, especially in <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, and in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, the logistics command for the national battle against forest fires, reported more than 25,000 firefighters, military and support personnel on the lines of more than three dozen major fires in the West. Fire Center spokesman <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartigan </PERSON> called it `` the most severe fire season in almost 30 years.'' More than 3.5 million acres have burned, two-thirds of that in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, and suppression costs already exceed $ 250 million. `` The fire season is anything but over. ... The 30-day weather forecast calls for continued unseasonably hot and dry weather for the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and northern Rockies,'' <PERSON> Hartigan </PERSON> said. Record highs were forecast during the weekend in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, with a threat of lightning. <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials asked people to stay out of forests in central <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and restrictions on such things as open campfires were tightened in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Many forests in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> were closed to recreational use. Logging activity was shut down statewide in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, on public and private land, because of fire concern. The <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> closed all its timberlands to public access until further notice. The focus of attention Friday in and around <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, where some 550,000 acres have been charred, was the small town of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, just outside the park's west entrance. It was threatened by flames just over a mile away that were spreading from the 118,000-acre North Fork fire inside the park that had grown by nearly 10,000 acres since Thursday morning. Bulldozers, helicopters and back fires stalled the advance of the fire Friday. But gusty winds swept a swath of flame south of the town and a wind change predicted for Monday raised concerns the blaze could move back toward the community. `` In my judgment this community is very defensible,'' <PERSON> Denny </PERSON> <PERSON> Bungartz </PERSON>, the North Fork fire's incident commander, told about 60 townspeople. He said firetrucks had pumped 5,000 gallons of water into dry brush around a warehouse at the park boundary, and 50 fire engines would be in town during the night to hose down buildings if necessary. To the east and north of town, the <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> formed a natural fire break. Firefighters improved on that barrier by bulldozing fire lines and lighting backfires, exhausting the forest's fuel before the main fire could reach the river, as helicopters dropped water on the area. Residents of the small town, with a year-round population of 750, prepared to evacuate but most stayed put Friday. Most of the people leaving town were tourists who decided to spend their Labor Day weekend somewhere less smoky. Curious onlookers filled the streets Friday as afternoon winds blew away the smoky haze. `` I'm packed up and ready to go,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, owner of a hamburger stand downtown. `` I left <LOCATION> L.A </LOCATION> because I could n't stand the smog. I do n't like this stuff.'' Some people were driving in the other direction, because West Yellowstone will play host to hundreds of square dancers this weekend for the Knothead Jamboree. Resident dance caller <PERSON> Orvile </PERSON> <PERSON> Pittam </PERSON> says it's been sponsored by square dance groups in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> every Labor Day weekend for 37 years and attracts up to 800 people. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Takata </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> president, said that while there have been some cancellations because of the fires, it's too early to tell what the overall effect will be. `` We want people to know that right now conditions are pretty good,'' he said Friday. `` We've had some bad press that <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> is being evacuated, and that's just not the case. We hope it will be business as usual.'' Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, the Clover Mist fire had covered 232,400 acres after growing 1,000 acres in 24 hours, the <LOCATION> Snake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> complex of fires was stable at about 156,500 acres and the <LOCATION> Wolf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> fire grew slightly to 40,500 acres, said fire information officer <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>. North of <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> in south-central <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, firefighters in the Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness changed their tactics Friday on a 49,800-acre wilderness fire that jumped fire lines four days in a row. Fire information officer <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Comstock </PERSON> said Friday that officals changed their strategy from building fire lines to setting backfires because `` our method of approach right now has n't been effective in catching this fire.'' Fire bosses in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> used a second day of light wind to gain more ground against the worst of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s 17 wildfires, with more than 3,000 firefighter and support personnel still battling fires that had burned more than 75,000 acres. Only the 40,300-acre Tepee Butte fire remained out of control in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, in the <ORGANIZATION> Wallowa-Whitman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> and the Hell's <ORGANIZATION> Canyon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recreation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> It was 25 percent contained Friday, officials said. By Friday, fires that raged through tinder-dry <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> forests were dying down, with all reported contained or under control. A new forest fire near <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> forced the evacuation of a few homes on Friday. The state's largest fire was a 2,000-acre blaze fanned by ridgetop winds near northern <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>'s Pineview Reservoir. The fire was initially declared under control late Tuesday at 525 acres but roared to life again late Wednesday when gusts fanned hot spots and pushed flames over fire lines.
