n the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> in April when a group of Jewish hikers clashed with <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> villagers. Police are investigating whether an 8-year-old boy slain August 27 near <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION> was killed by Palestinians. One reason Palestinian youngsters are so involved in protests is demographic: Almost 50 percent of the population of the occupied territories is 17 or younger, according to the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> research foundation. These are youngsters raised under the military rule <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has maintained over the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> since the territories were captured from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in 1967. Analysts say the young have become radicalized and are rebelling against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the traditional leadership of their elders, which failed to secure an independent state. `` It's a schoolyard revolution,'' said <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>, a U.N. Relief Works Agency official in the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. `` Even before the uprising, by March of 1987, if you were over 14 years old and had n't been arrested by the Israelis, you had n't got your school letter, to put it in American terms.'' Young people 18 to 25 are emerging as the new generation of leaders, and their younger siblings are followers and would-be successors, military sources said. `` Like the Americans of the 1960s who said, ` Do n't trust anyone over 30,' they are saying ` Do n't trust anyone over 25,''' <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> said. The Israeli army recently introduced plastic bullets in a move it says is intended to cut casualties. The army says its soldiers have orders not to open fire at children, but occupation rules consider those over age 14 accountable for their actions. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, an official of Save The Children, an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> relief organization, said the army should respect children's status as minors. `` Even if a kid is involved in a confrontation _ throwing a rock for example _ there is no justification for a well-equipped army to use lethal force,'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> said.
