<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Chiffons and the Orlons were female quartets, organized in 1960 to sing pop songs. The Taffetas are four women organized in 1988 to sing 1950s pop songs at the off-Broadway Cherry Lane Theater. The Taffetas, who pretend to be sisters, remind one most closely of the Lennon Sisters, of <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Welk </PERSON> reknown. Bubbles even stream up behind the Taffetas during their encore. It's an evening for smiling in the theater. In their pastel-colored gowns, with matching microphone cords and shoes, the Taffetas look like they're going to make fun of the'50s. They do n't. They do n't comment on the songs or update arrangements. They're going for nostalgia, in which the audience can look back with gentle, bemused affection. Those who do n't remember the'50s can view it like their parents' antiquated photo album. Those who do can try to recall who originally sang the songs. The Taffetas stress naivete, talking a lot about Mom and their home town of <LOCATION> Muncie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. They sing like crystalized sugar, only once digging with gusto into a lyric, `` Where the Boys Are.'' That song was sung originally by <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON>. The Taffetas also draw extensively from <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON> and <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Brewer </PERSON>. `` Mr. <PERSON> Sandman </PERSON>'' _ that was by the Chordettes. `` Dedicated to the One I Love'' _ the <LOCATION> Shirelles </LOCATION>. They do n't choose only from female soloists and quartets. `` Cry'' was a <PERSON> Johnnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> hit and the <ORGANIZATION> Ames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> first enlightened the world about `` Rag Mop,'' which the Taffetas take at a stately tempo. The singers are <PERSON> Jody </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrahams </PERSON>, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Curlee </PERSON>, <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tia </PERSON> <PERSON> Speros </PERSON>. Pianist <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, drummer <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Osrowitz </PERSON> and bassist <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> accompany. The show was conceived by <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and staged and choreographed by <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>. Like the mixed quartet in off-Broadway's `` Oil City Symphony,'' the Taffetas take time to talk about their hobbies. They are n't as clever as the `` Oil City'' four and their music is n't nearly as varied. Still, an evening with `` The Taffetas'' is a pleasant way, as they used to say on `` Your Hit Parade,'' to stroll down memory lane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
