<HEAD>President Delivers Peace Plan; Rebels Kill 12 Peasants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> offered Thursday to initiate peace talks with leftist guerrillas, who launched their second big attack in a week in northern <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> introduced his peace plan on national television. He said the talks should conclude with the dissolution of guerrilla organizations. Guerrillas must stop their terrorist acts, human rights violations, kidnappings and extortions before talks begin, <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> said. He said a peace agreement should be reached by the time of the next presidential and parliamentary elections, in March 1990. Guerrillas firing automatic assault rifles, throwing hand grenades and setting fire to houses killed 12 peasants Tuesday night, Gov. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> of the state of <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> said Thursday. The guerrilla attacks appear to be an effort by the rebels to force the government to open peace talks and make concessions. An estimated 30 guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> set fire to a ranch, killed 10 peasants and wounded 15 Tuesday near the town of <LOCATION> Canalete </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> said. Canalete is about 320 miles north of the capital of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. The insurgents then attacked the nearby village of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tomate </LOCATION>, setting fire to 26 huts and killing two people, the governor said in a broadcast interview with the Colombian radio chain <ORGANIZATION> RCN </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tomate </LOCATION>, a village of 600 people, the attackers left messages painted on walls declaring, `` Death to the toads and paramilitaries,'' survivors said in interviews with RCN. Guerrillas call army informants toads. Peasants in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> have long claimed that they are caught between the army and the guerrillas. In dozens of interviews with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, peasants have told of being forced to sell food and other necessities to guerrillas. Often the army hears of this and through threats or torture, soldiers force the peasants to tell of guerrilla movements, the peasants say. The guerrillas then return and kill the peasants, accusing them of being army informants, the peasants have said. The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and another guerrilla group known as the <ORGANIZATION> Colombian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> attacked the town of <LOCATION> Saisa </LOCATION> in the state of <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> on Aug. 23 and killed 12 civilians, 10 soldiers and two policemen, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said earlier. Twenty-two soldiers and policemen were taken prisoner, the ministry said.
