<HEAD>Computer Glitch Halts Discovery Astronauts' Simulated Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A simulated shuttle mission designed to test the Discovery astronauts' trouble-shooting skills was halted just before a mock landing because of a real-life computer crash, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The five astronauts were preparing to end their 56-hour mission Thursday afternoon by simulating a shuttle landing with a flat tire when the computer shutdown cut the rehearsal short. `` I'm sure they'll be looking at it to see why it went down, but nobody here considers it to be a big problem that the simulation ended early,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartsfield </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials stressed that there was no problem with any kind of computer used in actual flight control. In <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, meanwhile, engineers at <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday's fifth and final test of seals and joints on the space shuttle booster rocket lifted their confidence in parts redesigned after the Challenger disaster. `` Based on all appearances the test was a complete success,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, technical assistant to the manager of the solid rocket motor project. The two-minute static test firing, with the booster segment anchored in a $ 25 million test stand, put launch-style pressure on the redesigned joints. The seals are designed to keep internal hot gases inside the twin rockets that help kick shuttles into earth orbit. The failure of a joint in one of Challenger's two boosters was blamed for the January 1986 explosion that killed all seven crew members. Before the computer crash at <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, officials said, the Discovery crew handled all the simulated problems posed to them during a dress rehearsal for their flight, which is slated for late September or early October. The 56-hour mock mission began about an hour late Tuesday morning because of an earlier problem with the shuttle simulator. But other glitches faced by the Discovery crew were intentional, as commander <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauck </PERSON>, pilot <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Covey </PERSON> and mission specialists <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilmers </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Lounge </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> were placed in situations designed to test their ability to solve a multitude of problems that could encounter on an actual mission. Shortly after launch Tuesday, the astronauts were forced to alter their course and enter a low orbit after <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> trainers staged a main engine failure. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lounge </PERSON> had to go outside the orbiter to fix a stuck tilt-table needed to deploy a $ 100 million communications satellite. That simulation was done in a water tank, spokeswoman <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Selby </PERSON> said.
