<HEAD>Investigators Find Flap Handle Indicator in Wrong Position</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 5th graf, `Delta Flight ...,' with
deaths caused by smoke inhalation, survivor's comments.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SA1, DN9, DN10, DN12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators Thursday found the flap indicator handle on a shattered <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 in the wrong position, but a federal safety official said it could have been jarred that way in the fiery crash, which killed 13 people. The handle, which is located on the console between the pilot and the first officer, indicates the position of the aircraft's wing flaps At a news conference Thursday night, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said the handle on the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> jet that crashed Wednesday was found to be in the `` up position,'' opposite where it should have been for a proper takeoff. But he went on to say the handle could have been pushed into the wrong position by the impact or by a crew member during the plane's evacuation <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> Flight 1141 went down as it tried to take off from <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> en route to <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> with more than 100 people aboard. Most were able to escape the burning plane by crawling out of emergency exits or torn-open areas. All 13 deaths were attributed to smoke inhalation, according to the <LOCATION> Tarrant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> medical examiner's office, with burns also listed in two instances. One of the survivors, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Coester </PERSON>, 39, of the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION>, said he was most troubled by his unsuccessful efforts to rescue passengers trapped in the back of the burning plane. `` I tried to get the rear door open,'' said <PERSON> Coester </PERSON>, who was hospitalized for smoke inhalation and first -, second - and third-degree `` There was a handle on the outside. I got the door ajar, but not enough for them to get out.'' Investigators found at least five bodies near that door after the flames were extinguished. The same flight Thursday from <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> was aborted when the pilot detected a problem with his plane. Most of the 102 passengers, including six survivors of the crash Wednesday, left about two hours later on another plane, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> officials said. Federal investigators determined that the flaps and slats aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> MD-80 had not been properly set for takeoff when that plane crashed Aug. 16, 1987, at <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> Metropolitan airport, killing 156 people. <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> cautioned that the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigation team had just begun to study positions of the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> aircraft's wings and slats. <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigators said none of the witnesses they interviewed who were on nearby planes could tell them the position of the airplane's flaps. <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said investigators have not talked to the crew, but hoped to interview First Officer <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> on Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> official also said control tower personnel indicated the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 took off at an angle that was higher than normal. Control tower workers who watched the plane leaving told investigators the plane had a `` nose high attitude of 15 to 20 degrees.'' `` Investigators assume that they meant that was higher than normal,'' <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said. Earlier Thursday, <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> told reporters the plane's crew had another indication of trouble during takeoff. A cockpit tape recording recovered from the plane showed that pilots had talked about an engine problem seconds before the jetliner crashed. `` Shortly after takeoff there was a sound, -LRB- apparently a -RRB- warning a stall condition may be approaching,'' <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said. He said the sound came from the shaking of the `` stick,'' a device similar to the steering wheel that automatically makes a sound when a problem develops. `` This indicates the plane may be approaching a point where it wo n't be able to fly,'' he said. `` Shortly after that, there was some conversation about an engine problem.'' But he stressed that the warning sound could have stemmed from something besides an engine problem. He would not elaborate, except to say, `` In this case, we're talking about hydraulics.'' `` Every accident in its own way is unique,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>. `` You have to start from the beginning, put together a mosaic and slowly discover what went wrong.'' On Wednesday, the 15-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 failed to gain sufficient altitude, bounced three times on the runway and burst into flames. At least 95 people aboard miraculously survived by clambering or being pulled through emergency doors or through cracks in the burning fuselage into the hazy sunshine. `` Why? Why did it happen? That's the question we have to answer now,'' <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters Witnesses said there appeared to have been a fire or explosion in an engine on takeoff, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> said. `` But that was not confirmed,'' he said. `` This was merely what some witnesses were reporting.'' Thirty to 40 investigators from the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Whitney </LOCATION>, which manufactured the plane's three engines, fanned out over an area about the size of two football fields, examining pieces of the wrecked aircraft. Wearing gloves and carrying bags, some crawled inside the charred hulk, using the same cracks where passengers braved flaming jet fuel 24 hours earlier. They also climbed on the lone remaining attached wing, which had been turned red-hot by the fire, to peer into the cabin through blackened windows. At one point, about 20 of them gathered, peering intently at the left rear engine. They removed the engine shroud and looked inside. The cockpit recording, as well as the plane's flight data recorder, had already been recovered in good condition from the wreckage and taken to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for analysis. <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said safety board officials had listened to the cockpit tape recording just once, and they and other investigators planned to listen to again. The pilot, Capt. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, 48, of <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, was pinned in the wreckage and had to be extricated by rescuers. He was listed in fair condition Thursday at <ORGANIZATION> Parkland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, suffering back injuries and burns. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> has been a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> pilot since 1965 and a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 captain for nine years. His co-pilot and engineer also surviv