<HEAD>Human Rights Organization Launches Global Rock Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> says it hopes to raise the conscience of youth when <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>, and other rock stars launch a worldwide concert tour dedicated to human rights. The six-week tour, which opens tonight at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Wembley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION>, will go to 20 cities in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The $ 23 million extravaganza is to mark the 40th anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Declaration </ORGANIZATION> on Human Rights. Organizers expect sell-out crowds but stress that raising money is not the sole intention. `` This tour is not about charity, it's about justice,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Healey </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> division of the organization, which monitors human rights abuses and won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1977. `` What we're talking about is human rights and the seriousness of the issue ... there's too much torture, too many people being killed,'' he said. The pop stars taking part are both realistic and romantic about playing for human rights. `` When I was younger I thought maybe you could pick a guitar up and you could change the world,'' <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>, 38, said at a news conference Thursday. `` I do n't really believe that any more. But I do believe you can save a life,'' he added. `` Someone comes to the show, they hear the message, they hear what we are singing about, they go home, they write a letter and someone gets out of prison early. That's pretty good.'' <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON> is sharing a bill on the 35,000-mile tour with <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> and Sting, American folk singer <PERSON> Tracey </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sengal </PERSON>'s Youssou N'Dour More than 1 million people are expected to see the concerts live, with televison audiences of many more. Ticket prices vary from rich to poorer countries _ $ 37.60 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and $ 3 in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. The final concert is scheduled in the Argentine capital, <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, on Oct. 15. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sports goods manufacturer <ORGANIZATION> Reebok </ORGANIZATION> has underwritten the cost of the tour, and organizers say they hope it will break even. `` This is definitely not for fund-raising,'' said <PERSON> Healey </PERSON>, who put together a two-week American tour called `` Conspiracy of Hope'' in 1986 featuring <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>, Sting and an Irish group, U2. It convinced him that rock music works for human rights. Amnesty's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> membership rose by 100,000 to 250,000 in the year following the tour. The organization has a worldwide membership of 750,000. Every audience member will get a card with the text of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> declaration on human rights. Spectators will also be able to sign slips of paper saying they uphold the declaration. At the end of tour, Amnesty plans to deliver these to the governments of the nations visited. Amnesty's venture is the latest using rock music to raise consciences. Irish rock singer <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Geldof </PERSON>'s Live Aid concert in 1985 raised millions of dollars for the starving Ethiopians, and this year thousands turned out to mark South African black leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s 70th birthday with a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> concert. `` The reason we have an appeal for the young is, I believe, the fact that they are still able to say when they hear of an individual's plight, ` But that's not fair,''' said <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Staunton </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION>'s British section. <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>, a longtime campaigner for <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION>, said he agreed with critics that a song wo n't change the behavior of a dictator. `` But we hope it can affect the way his children and his grandchildren think. ... These are our target,'' said <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>.
