<HEAD>US Worried About Offensive Against Anti-Marxist Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is undertaking a major buildup of its forces in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, raising the possibility of a joint Cuban-Angolan offensive against U.S.-backed rebels, according to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials. With Cuban troop strength possibly exceeding 60,000, the officials said <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> may also be contemplating a cross-border strike into South African-controlled <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s southern neighbor. The Cuban buildup, accompanied by an estimated two dozen MiG23 fighter jets, helicopter gunships, tanks and other equipment, worries <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials who have been hoping for a negotiated withdrawal of the Cuban forces. Some officials believe that the Cubans may merely be attempting to improve their bargaining position at four-way talks aimed at achieving both a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> withdrawal and Namibian independence from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. But one official, speaking only on condition of anonymity, said the sheer numbers of Cubans and equipment involved in the buildup suggest that the Cubans are thinking more of a military offensive than a withdrawal. `` The numbers are frightening,'' the official said. The buildup began several weeks ago with about one ship a week loaded with troops and equipment undertaking the trans-Atlantic crossing. If the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> estimates are correct, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has increased its troop strength by about 25,000 since last November. The four-way talks involve officials from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> serving as mediator. The next round will take place next week in the Congolese capital of <LOCATION> Brazzaville </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> concluded the withdrawal of its troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> earlier this week and has said it will begin a withdrawal later this year from <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> provided <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> agrees to an early pullout from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. A South African pullback would set in motion a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> plan for the establishment of an independent government in the territory. The officials said the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> decided to withdraw from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> after recognizing that the Cuban buildup had changed the power balance in the southern part of the country, leaving South African troops vulnerable. They said South Africans may not even be a match for <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> forces in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> has been the colonial power for 73 years. One official said <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has 50 percent more tanks in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> than <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has in its entire inventory. As one official described it, <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> `` has his eye on the history books,'' possibly hoping to free <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> from South African control and to help defeat the anti-communist insurgency that has been operating in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> for 13 years. The <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> insurgency has received <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military support for the past three years and controls much of the southeastern part of the country. The four-way talks were convened last May in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at the suggestion of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>. At the time, officials said the parties appeared eager for a negotiated settlement, realizing that a military solution was impossible. But some officials now believe that <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has had in mind a military solution all along, and they say that theory has been bolstered by the Cuban buildup.
