<HEAD>Airlines Fined More Than $1 Million for Poor Security Inspections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government imposed more than $ 1 million in fines on 32 airlines for faulty airport security procedures as part of a stepped up effort to improve passenger screening. The fines announced Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> range from $ 1,000 against a number smaller, mainly commuter, airlines to $ 215,000 against <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 156,000 against <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and $ 113,000 against <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>. While the passenger screening at airport checkpoints usually is conducted by private security companies, the airlines hire the companies and are responsible for the program. The fines stem from <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> tests conducted at major airports nationwide in which agency inspectors carried phony weapons through airport security checkpoints without being detected, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said a recent audit of the security tests conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> showed improved screening, but nearly 15 percent of the phony weapons still passed through undetected. The 85.6 percent detection rate during the first six months of the year compares with a 78.9 percent rate during all of 1987, <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said. He added that some airport checkpoints detected more than 95 percent of the weapons in the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> tests, he said. But <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said that `` while the improvement in the detection rate is encouraging,'' tough enforcement measures, including civil penalties, are needed `` to insure industry-wide improvements and system-wide safety.'' Security lapses at airport checkpoints became a focus of attention last year when a congressional report chastized the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> for the screening system's shortcomings. The subject gained additional attention after a disgruntled former <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> employee smuggled a weapon aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet and began shooting, causing the plane to crash. All 43 people aboard the plane, which was flying from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, were killed. After the incident, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> announced it was using special teams of investigators to test security at 16 major airports. Last March, <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said the tests would improve the effectiveness of the screening programs. `` We want to see a 100 percent success rate in detecting weapons and dummy weapons,'' <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement Thursday. He promised to continue the airport tests. <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON>, meanwhile, indicated that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> may seek additional fines in the future if lapses are uncovered. `` We have no choice but to take tough enforcement action in those instances where security lapses are discovered,'' he said. Here are the airlines that were fined in the action announced Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 215,000; <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 156,000; <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 113,000; <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 96,000; <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 79,000; <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 67,000; <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 63,000; <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 61,000; <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, $ 58,000; <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, $ 51,000; <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 32,000; <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 31,000. <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 21,000; <ORGANIZATION> Sky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, each $ 20,000; <ORGANIZATION> Hawaiian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 12,000; <ORGANIZATION> Wings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Country </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Braniff </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, each $ 10,000; <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>, $ 3,000; <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 2,000. The following airlines each were fined $ 1,000: <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Midwest </ORGANIZATION>, Av Air, <ORGANIZATION> Brit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ComAir </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGAN