<TEXT>
 It was meant as a display of <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s youthful athleticism, but it took several tries for things to connect. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> helped the football team at <ORGANIZATION> Brandon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, run a few scrimmage plays Thursday, taking the role of quarterback for himself. The first pass was badly underthrown. The second made it to the receiver, but glanced off his fingertips. On third down, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> called for a new receiver and sent him out for a 15-yard pass. That time, the two connected. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, whose first two weeks as the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential career were about as rocky as his passing, acknowledged that his first pass was `` lousy.'' `` It's just like a campaign,'' he said. `` It's getting better and better.''
