<HEAD>Supreme Court Stays Contempt Citations Against Four Yonkers
Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf pvs, The council, with 4 grafs to show
councilmen faced jail and UPDATE with reaction from Yonkers mayor
and Cuomo. Picks up 9th graf, Federal Judge</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday night stayed a lower court ruling that had upheld contempt citations against four <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, city councilmen for fighting a federally ordered desegregation plan, a high court spokeswoman said. But in a related decision, the high court refused to stay a contempt ruling against the city. The court granted stays to council members <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Longo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chema </PERSON>, court spokeswoman <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON> said. `` The court has granted the stay for the four council members'' until they have had time to ask the court formally to fully review their cases, Ms. <PERSON> House </PERSON> said. `` The application so far as the city of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> is concerned has been denied,'' she added. She said the entire court considered the applications, and Justices <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> filed a 12-page dissent. On Friday, a federal appeals panel upheld a judge's contempt finding but gave the councilmen and <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> a week to seek an emergency stay from the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> before reinstating the penalties. The council members had faced $ 500-a-day fines and jail, and the city could be hit with $ 1 million a day in penalties. In <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, Mayor <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasicsko </PERSON> said early Friday, `` It seems at first curious that the fines would be stayed against the councilmen yet run against the city. It troubles me. The treasury of the city is going to be exposed and the taxpayers of the city are going to feel the burden. `` One thing it denies is the political martyrdom of the councilmen. They were slated to go to jail on Sunday. Their personal fines have ceased. But the city is going to plummet to bankruptcy. So their onus is their duty to the city. Their personal political martyrdom has been denied them.'' In <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON>, a spokesman for Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, said, `` The governor will review the decision and confer with his council. We wo n't have a comment before then.'' Federal Judge <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sand </PERSON> had found them in contempt Aug. 2, the day after the council first rejected the court-ordered desegregation plan by a 4-3 vote. The council members have refused three times to change their votes on a zoning amendment needed to carry out a housing plan that the council had accepted last January. Sand ordered the plan to remedy what he determined in a 1985 ruling to have been 40 years of deliberate segregation in housing and education in the city. The plan calls for 200 low-income public housing units to be built in the predominantly white east side of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, with 800 moderate-income apartments to be built throughout the city.
