<HEAD>Government Plans Research on Vehicle Rollovers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> says it will conduct research aimed at coming up with rules to protect the drivers of light vehicles from unreasonable risk of rollover. The <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> decision was announced Thursday in a case centering on the <ORGANIZATION> Suzuki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Samurai </ORGANIZATION>, under attack from consumer groups for an alleged tendency to roll over in curves. The safety board rejected a petition by the Center for Auto Safety, a consumers group that wanted a recall of the Samurai, saying the Samurai is no more likely to roll than other comparable vehicles. The agency, however, approved a petition from the <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> to study the light vehicle rollover problem in general. <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> responded to the decision by saying it showed that the allegations against the Samurai were unfounded. `` The federal government's action supports <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>'s claim that the Samurai is safe and should put to rest the inaccurate and misleading attacks on the vehicle,'' said a statement from the Japanese company's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suzuki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. About 169,000 Samurais have been sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> said The Center for Auto Safety, which is often at odds with automakers and their regulators, said the decision skirted the issue. `` If this were the law, then the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would refuse to prosecute one mass murderer because there are other mass murderers,'' the center said, citing reports of 113 rollovers, 120 injuries and 25 deaths involving the Samurai. The center said it would ask <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> to reconsider its decision. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said it granted the <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> petition because that request did not specify a single cause of Samurai rollovers and acknowledged that factors other than the stability of the vehicles lay behind some of the accidents. Many of the instances of rollover involving the Samurai happened when the driver had been drinking, was unfamiliar with the vehicle, or was attempting a risky maneuver, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> listed 10 research projects into vehicle stability it has completed or plans to complete, but said the research does not guarantee that new regulations will be issued. In rejecting the center's request for a Samurai recall, <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said the Samurai's rollover rate, based on a study of 1986 - and 1987-model vehicles, was six per 100,000 vehicles It said the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bronco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION>, by comparison, had a rollover rate of about 19 per 100,000 vehicles. The General Motors S-10 Blazer and S-15 <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> had rollover rates identical to the Samurai's. The Consumers Union in June urged a ban on the Samurai and, in its magazine Consumer Reports, rated the vehicle `` not acceptable,'' the first such rating given an automobile in 10 years. The ensuing publicity cut into Samurai sales and resulted in several lawsuits.
