<SECOND>PM-Cambodia Talks,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks On Cambodia Made Progress But No Breakthroughs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese and Soviet officials today said they found some common ground in just-concluded talks on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> but achieved no breakthroughs in resolving the 10-year Cambodian conflict. `` I'm satisfied with the negotiations we've had,'' Soviet Vice Minister <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogachev </PERSON> told reporters at the airport. `` We have now more common points, but that does not mean we have no points of difference.'' The Chinese deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> <PERSON> Zengpei </PERSON>, said the talks, which ended Thursday, were `` beneficial in deepening the mutual understanding between the two countries on their positions on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Rogachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tian </PERSON>, speaking to reporters at the airport before <PERSON> Rogachev </PERSON>'s departure for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, both refused to go into detail about the differences. The five-day meeting in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was the first time the two sides have met solely to discuss <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s 10-year occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Upon his arrival in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on Sunday, <PERSON> Rogachev </PERSON> said he thought a breakthrough in resolving Chinese-Soviet differences on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> was at hand. The Cambodian problem is the major barrier to normalization of relations between the two communist giants and to their first summit in 29 years. The nations severed relations in the early 1960s over strategic and ideological differences. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the chief backer of the anti-Vietnamese resistance in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, has called on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which supports <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, to pressure <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> for an early and total withdrawal of its troops. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> in May agreed to withdraw 50,000 troops by the end of this year and its remaining forces by 1990. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has repeatedly expressed doubt over the sincerity of the Vietnamese promise, and <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> was skeptical about next year's pullout `` We will wait and see what they do,'' he said. According to <PERSON> Tian </PERSON>, the Soviets agreed `` in principle'' with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s stand that a four-party coalition government, made up of the three resistance factions and the Hanoi-established government in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>, should be set up following <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s withdrawal. <PERSON> Rogachev </PERSON> said only, `` We will approve the decision that will be taken by the -LRB- Cambodians -RRB- themselves. -LRB- They -RRB- must decide.'' <PERSON> Rogachev </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> issue will be taken up by the Soviet and <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> foreign ministers at a meeting in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> later this month. He added that another round of talks would be held next year, but a date and place have not been decided.
