<FIRST>r a PM-CDC--Measles     09-02 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC--Measles,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Measles Going Back Down For First Time In Four Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After three years on the increase, measles is on its way down again, but health experts say it's too early to tell if the disease might finally be on the decline for good. The national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that 3,652 cases of the once-common childhood disease were reported in 1987, down 42 percent from the previous year. It's the first drop in measles reporting since the record low of 1,497 cases in 1983. Measles has fallen 99 percent since the era before measles vaccine was licensed in 1963, and the disease was thought headed for eradication when the record low came in 1983. But the case count then surprised researchers by going back up in 1984,'85 and'86. Researchers can not say just what the latest drop in measles really means, said Dr. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> measles specialist. The disease could continue to show `` little peaks and valleys'' for the next decade, he noted. `` We do n't really know,'' he said. `` We feel now that the vaccine is very good and very effective, but there are problems we are having _ in the people unvaccinated in the inner cities, and the vaccine failures in the school-age children.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said 1,010 of the cases, or 28 percent, were theoretically preventable, occurring in people who should have been vaccinated, but were n't _ mostly preschool children in urban areas. Nearly three-fourths of the cases _ 2,642 _ were classified as non-preventable, occurring in patients who had been vaccinated but got measles anyway; most of those patients were older schoolchildren. `` We've got two fronts,'' <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> said, `` the -LRB- young -RRB- kids in those preventable cases, and the vaccine failure in older children.'' The Atlanta-based agency said Thursday its expert consultants still believe the elimination of measles in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` should be pursued,'' but the two lingering problems _ the non-vaccinated and the vaccine failures _ will `` require different solutions.'' `` Increased efforts are needed to vaccinate preschool-aged children,'' particularly in inner-city areas, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said in its weekly report. `` Innovative strategies are needed to increase immunization levels in these populations.'' Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said, `` aggressive revaccination strategies'' may be needed during measles outbreaks to eliminate the so-called non-preventable cases in already-vaccinated children. Such a revaccination would involve a rapid program of additional shots for most children vaccinated before 1980, when new vaccination recommendations and new vaccine techniques began to improve the protection somewhat, <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> said. Twenty-nine percent of last year's cases occurred among patients under 5; another 29 percent occurred in the 15-19 age group. Researchers have reports on how two-thirds of the patients got the measles; 53 percent of them acquired the disease in primary and secondary schools, while others picked it up in day care, universities, at home or in other settings. Three-fourths of the cases _ 2,759 _ were reported from eight locations: <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, 469 cases; <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, 809; <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, 452; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, 318; <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, 213; <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, 190; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, 162; and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, 146. Fewer than 9 percent of the nation's counties reported measles cases.
