<FIRST>r a PM-AgentOrange     09-02 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agent Orange,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Vietnam Vets Escaped Heavy Exposure to Dioxin, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A veterans group criticized a new report by the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> that suggests most <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> GIs escaped heavy exposure to the poison dioxin, unless they handled the herbicide Agent Orange. `` This study seems to be pretty much the same data that was released a year ago, only a year ago it was portrayed rather differently,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasinitz </PERSON>, a spokesman for the 35,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Vietnam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> last year concluded that exposure to dioxin could not be determined using military records of troop locations and spraying of Agent Orange, which contained the deadly poison. `` Now ... they are jumping to the conclusion that very few people were exposed,'' <PERSON> Kasinitz </PERSON> said Thursday in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` That was a bit of a jump in logic that does n't seem to be substantiated.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s new report, in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, describes a comparison of blood tests between 646 <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans and 97 non-Vietnam veterans. `` Current TCDD -LRB- dioxin -RRB- levels were nearly identical in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and non-Vietnam veterans,'' the researchers said. The latest study deliberately drew <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans from battalions that had served in areas most heavily sprayed with Agent Orange around <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION> in 1967 and 1968, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. Only two <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans, or 0.3 percent of all 646 tested, had blood dioxin levels greater than 20 parts per trillion, considered `` clearly elevated,'' the researchers said. `` These two men each reported their health status as ` excellent' and did not attribute any health problems to Agent Orange exposure,'' the researchers added The two men were not among the 14 percent of the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans in the study group who did link health problems to exposure. `` This study is consistent with other studies and suggests that most <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> ground troops who served in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> were not heavily exposed to <ORGANIZATION> TCDD </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- dioxin -RRB-, except perhaps men whose job involved handling herbicides,'' the researchers said. But <PERSON> Kasinitz </PERSON> said the new report gives the `` unfortunate'' impression that small exposures to dioxin were harmless, which has not been proven, `` and that there is no need for the government to act to assist those that have been harmed.'' Dioxin stays in the bloodstream for many years, and high levels of the chemical can be measured with blood tests as long as two decades after someone has been exposed, the researchers said. Agent Orange was used as a defoliant in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> during the 1960s by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military. Some <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans contend it has caused them such health problems as cancer, immune system disorders and birth defects in their children. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> just two months ago cleared the last legal obstacle to a multimillion-dollar settlement that could benefit up to 250,000 <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans in a class-action lawsuit against the seven manufacturers of Agent Orange. But scientists are still trying to settle a continuing controversy over exactly what health effects the dioxin in Agent Orange may have. Dioxin is known to be one of the most powerful causes of cancer in laboratory animals ever tested. It has not been shown to cause cancer in humans, but the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> classifies it as a probable carcinogen.
</TEXT>
