<FIRST>r a PM-Whitworth     09-02 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whitworth,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whitworth Espionage Convictions, Sentence Affirmed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court upheld the espionage convictions and 365-year prison sentence of ex-Navy radioman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON>, a member of the Walker spy ring that passed military secrets to the Soviets. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled 3-0 Thursday that the punishment fit <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON>'s crime of selling ultra-sensitive <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> decoding and communications information to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The sentence imposed by U.S. District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Vukasin </PERSON> `` viewed in the abstract ... would appear harsh,'' the court said. `` This sentence, however, is not disproportionate to <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON>'s crimes. <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON>, 49, of <LOCATION> Davis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a radioman with a top-secret clearance for much of his 18-year <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> career, was convicted in 1986 of seven counts of espionage for supplying ultra-sensitive decoding and communications information to spymaster <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> for nearly a decade, in exchange for $ 332,000. <PERSON> Vukasin </PERSON> called <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON> `` one of the most spectacular spies of the century'' and imposed the nation's harshest sentence for espionage since <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, convicted of conspiring to furnish atomic bomb secrets to the Soviets, were electrocuted in 1953. <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON>'s sentence forbids parole consideration for 60 years. In the decision, the court rejected defense arguments that a sentence longer than <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s amounted to cruel and unusual punishment. Military and intelligence officials testified at the trial that the spy ring had revealed the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s most precious secrets and caused damage that may be impossible to calculate. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> also recruited his son and brother as members of the spy ring. He pleaded guilty in a <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> federal court to spying for the Soviets for 17 years and was sentenced to life in prison, with parole possible in 10 years. The opinion by Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Boochever </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution does not require a judge in one court to compare a defendant's relative guilt to that of a defendant in another court on separate charges before imposing sentence Even if comparison of guilt was required, <PERSON> Boochever </PERSON> said, `` the court notes that <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON> kept <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s espionage operation alive for nearly a decade and himself became a central figure because of his access to highly classified material.'' <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON>'s chief prosecutor, former Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, commented, `` The sentence was not harsh at all. If this had been a case where there was a death penalty available, it clearly would have been prosecuted as a capital case.'' Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Svetcov </PERSON>, who represented the prosecution on appeal, agreed that <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON> deserved a death sentence, which was abolished for espionage and other federal crimes by a 1972 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling. `` It's a sickness in our society, that we have people willing to do harm to their own country for money,'' <PERSON> Svetcov </PERSON> said. `` These guys were not Communists by any means. They were strictly in it for profit.'' <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON>'s lawyer on appeal, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, said he was disappointed by the ruling and would appeal. He said he was `` astounded'' by the court's conclusion that the verdict was not influenced when <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> was improperly allowed to speculate on the witness stand that <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON> must have known the secrets were being delivered to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, also a former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> radioman with a top-secret clearance, testified that he had started selling secrets to a Soviet agent in 1968 and recruited <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON> as his chief supplier of classified materials in 1974, after <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> himself no longer had direct access to the material. <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON> was convicted of furnishing to <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> the secrets of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> decoding equipment, code keys and communications systems that <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON> gathered and photographed for nearly a decade as a highly placed radio officer at ship and shore stations.
</TEXT>
