<HEAD>Ammunition For Olympic Event Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police said today they were investigating whether some missing bullets meant for an Olympic shooting competition may be in the hands of terrorists. They said customs officials in the southern city of <LOCATION> Pusan </LOCATION> unsealed a container on a ship and discovered that 400 rounds of ammunition were missing. The Japanese-registered <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bridge </ORGANIZATION>, which was loaded in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, docked in <LOCATION> Pusan </LOCATION> on Thursday. Police said the ship sailed from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on Aug. 31 with 25,000 rounds of ammunition for the shooting competition. They said they were investigating whether the bullets may have been turned over to terrorists trying to disrupt the Olympics, which are to to be held in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> from Sept. 17 to Oct. 2. Security has been one of the prime concerns surrounding the Games, and stiff measures are being enforced near all ports of entry.
