<FIRST>r a PM-Carlucci-Reform     09-02 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carlucci-Reform,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carlucci: Congress Must Help Reform Procurement Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER BRANDLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> warned <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> not to act hastily to change the way it reviews defense spending in the wake of a major fraud probe involving defense contractors and consultants. Lawmakers should not adopt reform proposals being circulated on Capitol Hill, including creation of an independent acquisition agency, removing the inspector general from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> and locking the `` revolving door'' between the <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> and defense contractors, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said on Thursday. `` Certainly, we want to see those found guilty of wrongdoing punished, and punished severely, for their actions ... but reform is really about prevention, not punishment,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. The speech before the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Foreign Affairs was the most comprehensive statement to date by the secretary since revelations of a widespread investigation of alleged fraud involving defense contractors and consultants. In his `` prescription for procurement reform,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> called on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to simplify its budget-making process, reduce the number of committees that oversee defense spending, shift the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget to a two-year cycle and provide multi-year funding for more weapon programs. The goal should be to limit the number of `` intervention points where a skillful lobbyist can succeed'' in gaining an advantage, he said. `` Right now, the defense budget bill must complete a 17-step process to final passage,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. `` Each point along the way is an opportunity for those bent on exerting improper influence.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must seek ways `` to reduce the profusion of intervention points on -LRB- <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> -RRB- that invite improper _ if not always strictly illegal _ behavior,'' he said. However, Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the speech failed to address central issues of procurement `` Since the procurement scandal erupted, we have seen people selling old ideas that have nothing to do with the procurement problem,'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. `` They are pet rocks dressed up as solutions to the scandal. But they are still pet rocks. I am afraid Secretary <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> has fallen into the same trap in his speech billed ` prescription for procurement reform. `` His proposal dealt with budget reform, not procurement reform. His suggestions say nothing about the use of consultants, the abuse of insider information, or restoration of the integrity of the bidding process,'' the congressman said. `` Many of his suggestions for budget reform are valid and have been pushed by me and others over the years. But they have nothing to do with procurement reform,'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation, which became public in June, centers on allegations that defense contractors routinely used outside consultants to obtain proprietary information on the bids of competitors, and that the consultants may have paid bribes to <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> employees. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> warned against a `` legislative rush'' to enact reforms without considering their effects. `` At the very least, <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION>'s critics owe us a hearing before they try to pass legislation that could impact our procurement process and the defense industrial base for years to come,'' he said. `` We need to ask: How does the system as it exists today offer wrongdoers the opportunity to act _ and how can we close these windows of vulnerability in the procurement process?'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said establishment of an independent acquisition agency by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would erect barriers between the acquisition process and those in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> who know best what weapons they need. Likewise, the defense department relies on the `` revolving door'' that brings experts from the industry into government, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. `` We need to police the system for abuses, not penalize procurement professionals for seeking to build on and benefit from their expertise,'' he said. As for the suggestion that the inspector general should be removed from the <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said it would `` deprive the secretary of defense of the eyes and ears that help him monitor the system he is charged with supervising.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> already has acted to prevent contractors from winning contracts unfairly by streamlining its own acquisitions chain of command, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said.
