<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 300 students protested today to demand that the Olympics be shared with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, and they claimed the Games were being used to increase dictatorial rule. Officials said that President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo plans to release dissidents from prison after the Olympics. Students from several colleges in the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> area took part in the rally at <ORGANIZATION> Hongik </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and said they would `` not sit idle'' during the Olympics. But they did not say if they would attempt to disrupt the Games. `` We oppose the Olympics, which only help dictator <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo,'' the students shouted. Government officials are concerned radicals may stage protests during the Sept. 17-Oct. 2 event The radicals have little public support and have been strongly criticized by many Koreans in recent weeks for staging violent demonstrations. The one-hour rally and short march today were peaceful. Dozens of students took up positions in front of the school for possible clashes with police, but riot police stayed away. The students shouted slogans supporting <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s demand to be a co-host at the Games. `` Let's advance national unification by co-hosting the Olympics!'' the students chanted. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has said it will boycott the Olympics unless it is allowed to be a co-host. The International Olympic Committee said the Games can not be shared because they are awarded to a single city. Radical students, a small but powerful minority on campuses, are seeking to topple the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> government. They have become increasingly pro-leftist as they have lost support among most students and other Koreans following broad democratic reforms by the government. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nor