<HEAD>President Offers Peace Plan With Guerrillas In National Address</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>, in a national address, offered to start peace talks with leftist guerrillas who have attacked two northern <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> towns within a week. <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> told a national television audience Thursday night that the talks should conclude with the dissolution of guerrilla organizations. Guerrillas must stop their terrorist acts, human rights violations, kidnappings and extortions before talks begin, <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> said. He said a peace agreement should be reached by March 1990, when the next presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled. The offer came two days after guerrillas firing automatic assault rifles, throwing hand grenades and setting fire to houses killed 12 peasants, Gov. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> state said. An estimated 30 guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> set fire to a ranch, killed 10 peasants and wounded 15 Tuesday near the town of <LOCATION> Canalete </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> said Thursday. Canalete is about 320 miles north of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. The insurgents then attacked the nearby village of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tomate </LOCATION>, setting fire to 26 huts and killing two people, the governor said in a broadcast interview with the Colombian radio chain <ORGANIZATION> RCN </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tomate </LOCATION>, a village of 600 people, the attackers left messages painted on walls declaring, `` Death to the toads and paramilitaries,'' survivors said in interviews with RCN. Guerrillas call army informants toads. Peasants in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> have long claimed that they are caught between the army and the guerrillas. In dozens of interview