<HEAD>Hong Kong Planning New Shelter For Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said today it will build a new emergency shelter for the growing number of Vietnamese refugees arriving by boat to this British colony. The center, which is to open by the end of September, will be the sixth center built to house Vietnamese boat people who landed after mid-June. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> announced a new policy that classified most of the boat people who arrived after June 15 as illegal immigrants subject to repatriation. Vietnamese who arrived earlier are considered political refugees eligible for resettlement. More than 9,000 new refugees _ including 2,375 in August _ arrived since the measure took effect, although it was designed to stop the rising influx of boat people. The number of Vietnamese in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> refugee camps totals 25,000, according to government statistics. The new center is expected to shelter about 3,000 people in huts, the government said. Some residents near the site of the future shelter said they will oppose it unless authorities guarantee local services will not be disrupted, government-run radio reported. <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> said it will examine on a case-by-case basis the Vietnamese who arrived in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> after mid-June, if they volunteer to return to their homeland, 500 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. However, only 1 percent of the boat people have requested repatriation to their communist homeland, and none has returned so far, a government spokeswoman said today. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees is processing their applications to return.
