<HEAD>Coast Guard Sends Icebreaker to Help Cruise Ship in Beaufort Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An intellectuals' cruise ship trapped in the ice inside the <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circle </ORGANIZATION> awaited a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> icebreaker today. The 149 passengers and crew members were in no danger, the cruise operator said. Passengers on the Society Explorer bound for the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Passage </ORGANIZATION> were paying an average of $ 400 a day as clients of a company specializing in educational journeys to unconventional destinations, including <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said the 236-foot ship was caught in <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> ice 50 miles northeast of Point Barrow, or about 400 miles inside the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>. The crew notified Canadian maritime officials on Wednesday the ship was stranded. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that one of its icebreakers, based in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, was bound for the area on a research mission and was diverted to help the cruise vessel. The 399-foot icebreaker was expected to reach the ship Saturday. The Society Explorer set sail from <LOCATION> Dutch </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> on Aug. 19. Stops have included the <LOCATION> Pribilof </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gambell </PERSON> and the Siberian port of <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION>. The itinerary calls for the ship to sail east along the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Passage </LOCATION>, with the voyage scheduled to end in St. <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s, <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, on Sept. 21. That schedule likely will be set back several days, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, planning director for <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Expedition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cruises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, which offers trips that emphasize libraries and lectures. The passengers, most of them Americans, found intellectual pursuits to fill the time while awaiting the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. `` Our entertainment on board is mostly intellectual entertainment, not gambling and dancing,'' <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said. He said the company caters to an `` extremely well-educated and a very naturalist-oriented passenger.'' He said the ship is `` absolutely safe'' and well-stocked with items on its continental menu. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> likened the <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> to `` a big jigsaw puzzle'' of ice and water. A wind rearranged the ice to the ship's disadvantage, said <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON> of North Slope Borough Search and Rescue. The rescue unit planned to fly over the ship for a look but was held back by heavy fog Thursday, <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON> said. Employees of an Alaskan air-service company who flew over the vessel on Wednesday said it was caught in seven to eight miles of ice.
