<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUGHMACRORY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police guarded a funeral service in this village today for two <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas killed by British soldiers, and rioting occurred for a second night in <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> west <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>. Black flags were hung on telephone poles and pro-IRA slogans were scrawled on walls in <LOCATION> Loughmacrory </LOCATION>, 45 miles west of <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>. Brothers <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON>, 29, and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON>, 21, were to be buried after a service at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, and 26-year-old <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON>'s funeral was to be held Saturday at the nearby village of <LOCATION> Dunmoyle </LOCATION>. Police said they were shot and killed in a British army ambush Tuesday and that the trio was plotting to kill an off-duty soldier. Dozens of police with riot shields and batons deployed in the village and along the road to the <PERSON> Harte </PERSON> family home, apparently to prevent the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> turning the funeral into an anti-British show of strength. The <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> said it honored its dead comrades with a ceremonial volley in the <LOCATION> Loughmacrory </LOCATION> area Thursday night. In <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, a police spokesman who demanded anonymity said police fired plastic bullets to disperse rioters during violence in Roman Catholic areas of the city that flared Thursday night and continued early today. Police said that in rioting earlier Thursday in a west <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> IRA stronghold, three people were slightly injured and taken to the hospital when troops fired plastic bullets at a hostile crowd. Police said the rioting in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> late Thursday and early today was not on the scale of riots that broke out Wednesday. In those riots, gangs of young <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> supporters set fire to a bus, two vans and more than 35 cars, and hurled gasoline bombs and rocks at security forces while a gunman fired on the city's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barnsley </LOCATION> police station. Dozens of burned out vehicles still blocked some roads in the area Thursday night as groups of youths gathered at street corners, talking and drinking beer while police and army patrols cruised by. Police said the three slain <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> men were armed, masked and driving in a stolen car when they were ambushed. They said <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON> was the commander of the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Mid-Tyrone </ORGANIZATION> unit and that <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON> was responsible for selecting <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> targets from the ranks of the police and the <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regiment </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON> was arrested during police raids following the Aug. 20 bus bombing but was released without charge, they said. The <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> in a statement Wednesday said the <PERSON> Harte </PERSON> brothers and <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON>, 26, were on `` active service'' _ a guerrilla euphemism for a bombing or shooting mission _ when they were slain. The mainly <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> is fighting to end British rule in Protestant-dominated <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and unite it with the mainly <LOCATION> Catholic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> under socialist rule. Organizers of Sport Aid, a worldwide charity run scheduled for Sept. 11, announced that the army had withdrawn from participation in an event at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hyde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, citing the heightened <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> threat to military personnel.
