<HEAD>Stag Brewery Closes, Ending 130-Year Tradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's last call for Stag Beer. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Galati </PERSON> pushed the last case of beer off the <ORGANIZATION> Stag </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewery </ORGANIZATION> production line at 1 p.m. Thursday, ending a brewing era in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. `` As the final case came through, a lot of memories flashed in my mind,'' said <PERSON> Galati </PERSON>, a machine operator at <LOCATION> Stag </LOCATION> for 11 years. `` I felt bad. It was a depressing moment for me.'' <PERSON> Stag </PERSON> was <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>' last full-scale brewery, and at 130 years was one of the oldest in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. The closing put about 200 people out of work. <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heileman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns Stag, announced June 27 its was closing the brewery because of its age, excess capacity at other <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> plants and the need to spend $ 2.9 million for a sewage plant for the brewery. The LaCrosse, Wis.-based beer company and <LOCATION> Belleville </LOCATION> officials continue to search for investors willing to reopen the brewery. Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Brauer </PERSON> said last week an unidentified investor was considering making an offer to buy the brewery. But <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Perleberg </PERSON>, director of planning and development for <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON>, said Thursday, `` We have received no offers and I have no comment further than that.'' <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> bought the brewery from <ORGANIZATION> Carling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Breweries </ORGANIZATION> in 1979. Last fall, Australian brewing giant <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> purchased <PERSON> Heileman </PERSON> for $ 1.22 billion The company closed a brewery in <LOCATION> Evansville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, earlier this year. Workers who trickled out of the Stag plant Thursday said they were resigned to the closing. `` It was very quiet at work today,'' said <PERSON> Galati </PERSON>, 34. `` There was a lot of hugging and hand-shaking. ... I'm going to miss the money and working with the guys. I've been working with some of these guys for so long, I'll miss seeing them every day.'' About 180 employees had been laid off by Thursday. The remaining 50 will be kept on indefinitely to handle distribution of the remaining stock, close the books and maintain equipment in hopes an investor will save the plant. <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Beaston </PERSON>, 27, said his grandfather, father and four brothers have worked at the brewery. He said he hopes the brewery is reopened soon. `` The shorter the time it is shut down, the quicker it can be started back up,'' <PERSON> Beaston </PERSON> said.
