<HEAD>Feuding Black Organizations Sign Pact To End Conflict</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5-6 grafs pvs, ``The agreement...of violence.'' with 4
grafs to UPDATE with details of agreement. Pickup 7th graf pvs,
``Most of...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Feuding black political organizations today signed an agreement aimed at ending the country's bloodiest ongoing conflict, in which more than 600 people have died in 20 months. The fighting in <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> has pitted supporters of militant anti-apartheid organizations against members of <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION>, a more conservative group headed by prominent Zulu leader <PERSON> Mangosuthu </PERSON> <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>. Inkatha's secretary general, <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Dhlomo </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Naidoo </PERSON>, secretary general of the militant <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions, signed the agreement at a courthouse in the provincial capital, <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION>. The labor federation, known as <ORGANIZATION> COSATU </ORGANIZATION>, has been allied with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a now-banned anti-apartheid coalition, in the feud against <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION>. The agreement condemns violence and calls for formation of a conciliation board which would review residents' complaints of harassment or attacks. The board's members would be selected jointly by the two sides and have disciplinary powers. As part of the agreement, each side will drop pending court cases accusing the other of violence. `` Each party recognizes the immediate necessity to make it abundantly clear to its members that <ORGANIZATION> COASTU </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION> categorically condemn acts of intimidation, forced recruitment and violence,'' the agreement says. `` All political organizations have the right to exist and the <ORGANIZATION> democratic </ORGANIZATION> right to espouse their own particular viewpoint,'' it says. Most of the fighting has been in the black townships around <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION> but has spread in recent months to townships near the larger port city of <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>. Many of the killings have been to avenge earlier killings. Both Inkatha, which claims 1.5 million members, and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> Front-COSATU alliance oppose the apartheid policies which enable <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 5 million whites to dominate 26 million blacks. But their strategies differ markedly. The front, a predominantly black coalition of about 600 groups, advocates economic sanctions, strikes and other confrontational measures to bring about sweeping political and economic change. Inkatha opposes sanctions, avoids militant protest and advocates capitalism. Many militants view <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> as a government collaborator because he is chief minister of the <ORGANIZATION> KwaZulu </ORGANIZATION> homeland. However, <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> has rejected invitations by the government to join in negotiating reforms that would expand blacks' political role while leaving whites in ultimate control. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerschoff </PERSON>, a social worker in <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION> who has been involved in past reconciliation efforts, said the agreement was an important but not final step toward ending the conflict. Because of government bans and restrictions `` it is extremely difficult for <ORGANIZATION> COSATU </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> UDF </ORGANIZATION> to communicate with grassroots people. This will have to be addressed,'' he said in a telephone interview. The <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> violence has distressed other anti-apartheid campaigners and caused debate over whether black political groups could avoid factional fights and effectively oppose the white-led government. Some commentators viewed the conflict as a harbinger of widespread black infighting that might develop as black groups with different ideologies struggled for supremacy.
</TEXT>
