<TEXT>
 An `` extremely cautious'' <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> pilot aborted takeoff when a panel indicator warned of possible engine trouble on Flight 1141, on which a jet crashed and burned a day earlier. Six people aboard aborted Flight 1141 Thursday were among the 95 survivors of Wednesday's crash at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, which killed 13. The doomed plane also was a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727. `` He was only at a maximum of 20 knots -LRB- 23 mph -RRB- ... which is pretty slow for an airplane,'' said <PERSON> Glenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` Then he gets an indicator on the panel that there is a momentary disruption of air flow'' in one of the engines. `` The captain feels that he had what is called a compressor stall,'' said another <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>. `` There was a crosswind blowing across the runway. That can interrupt the smoothness of the airflow that goes into the engine, creating a temporary loss of power.'' Under normal circumstances, a pilot would `` simply increase thrust to see if everything continued to perform right. But based on the incident that happened yesterday, the captain was extremely cautious and elected simply to come back to the gate and let maintenance look at the engine,'' <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said. On any day, <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said, captains `` have got to go by their years of experience'' and can abort flights `` if they do n't like what they feel, if they've just got a gut feeling.'' <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> declined to release the pilot's name. Today, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> Flight 1141 departed Dallas-Fort Worth without inc