 <LOCATION> WINDHOEK </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> today denied it planted a bomb at a hotel patronized by blacks and blamed <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The blast killed two people and injured 15, police said. The three-story Continental Hotel was severely damaged by the explosion Thursday evening. Witnesses said parked cars were hurled across the street. About one mile away, a mine exploded 90 minutes later on a railroad line, but no one was injured, police said. Hospital officials earlier had said two people were hurt in the blast. The <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>, has fought since 1966 for independence for the South Africa-ruled territory. It issued the denial from its office in <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, and called the bombing one of `` <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s dirty tricks.'' The statement said: `` It is not <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>'s policy to attack soft targets. This bomb attack was aimed at demoralizing white Namibians and setting them against <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>.'' The explosions occurred on the day <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> said it would begin a voluntary cease-fire. The organization has fought a long guerrilla war against South African control of <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. The government-run broadcasting network said an anonymous telephone 