<HEAD>Lawmakers Finish Brazil's New Constitution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislators today completed a l9-month process of drafting a new constitution to replace an authoritarian document handed down two decades ago by the military regime. The document shortens presidential terms to five years, abolishes cencorship, guarantees the right of workers to strike and rejects land reform. Elated lawmakers in the constituent assembly sang the national anthem and threw confetti into the air when speaker <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON> <PERSON> Guimaraes </PERSON> closed the final sesion at 1:49 a.m. `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is a new country,'' <ORGANIZATION> Guimaraes </ORGANIZATION> said. `` This constitution will protect the weak and punish those who abuse power.'' The final version appeared to be a mixture of radical, even nationalistic laws on foreign and domestic business and mainly conservative laws on issues such as land reform. Since February 1987, legislators have been working on the new charter, which replaces the 19-year-old constitution handed down by military generals during a 1964-1985 military regime. The new 245-article charter is to go into effect Sept. 23. It will be <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s eighth constitution in 166 years of independence. The 559 representatives and senators chosen in wide-ranging 1986 elections have been voting for several weeks on the more than 1,000 amendments to the 245-article final draft, which was completed in July. The draft itself was the result of more than a year of voting on an initial draft of more than 3,000 articles, derided by many because of its length. Over the past 19 months, legislators engaged in heated and often even violent debate over such controversial issues as land reform, the system of government <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> should adopt, the presidential term and the right to strike. Some of the key decisions are: _ President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> and future presidents will serve for five years, in contrast to the six-year term of former military presidents _ Censorship, a remnant of military days, was abolished in films, books and television _ The right to strike was guaranteed for all workers Before, `` essential'' sectors of the labor force were not allowed to strike. _ The assembly rejected wide-ranging land reform in a country where four percent of the people own 50 percent of the farmable land This countered a government promise to distribute land to 1.4 million landless peasant farmers. _ Decree law, a powerful tool used by the president to bypass <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and push through legislation, was also abolished _ The voting age was lowered from 18 to 16 years of age The only other country where 16 year olds can vote is <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. _ Maternity leave for new mothers was extended from 90 to 120 days and the work week was cut from 48 to 44 hours _ A 12 percent ceiling was imposed on interest rates charged above inflation Interest rates have been running as high 1,000 percent yearly, while inflation this year is expected to reach 700 percent. _ Mineral mining was nationalized and foreign companies now involved in mining will have to leave <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> in four years or transfer financial control to residents of the country _ New oil risk contracts allowing foreign companies to drill in oil-rich <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> were banned
