<HEAD>Some Residents Leave West Yellowstone Community As Labor Day
Weekend Opens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with morning conditions near
West Yellowstone; CLARIFIES that residents left rather than fled;
PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `Earlier Thursday ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents of a tourist town outside <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> left overnight as a `` slop-over'' wildfire moved to within 1 -LCB- miles. Elsewhere in the West, campers were barred from the woods as the Labor Day weekend opened. Wildfires also burned over hundreds of thousands of acres in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, residents and tourists filled their gas tanks as flames to the west lit up the sky with an orange glow Thursday night. `` There are some pretty nervous people, no question about that,'' said <PERSON> Dawn </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitman </PERSON>, a gas station owner. The threat came from a quarter - to half-acre `` slop-over'' of a 109,100-acre fire inside the park As the flames progressed, residents watched smoke billow high into the air. Explosions set off by firefighters cutting fire lines periodically shook buildings. `` The town was pretty excited last night,'' <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, said this morning. `` Things have calmed down a little. No evacuation has been ordered, but we do have an evacuation plan in case one is necessary.'' Earlier Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s south gate reopened for the first time in almost two weeks, leaving all park entrances and roads open. In eastern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, recreational users were banned from 3.8 million acres of state-protected land beginning today. Already closed are 2.8 million acres in western <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, lighter wind allowed firefighters breathing room on the worst of 17 blazes, but activities were restricted in several forests over the Labor Day weekend. Tight controls also were placed on campfires in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. `` It's like sitting on a time bomb,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, recreation officer for the <ORGANIZATION> Sawtooth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recreation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> in central <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. `` If we can get through this weekend without a conflagration, it will be a miracle.'' Progress was reported on two other major series of fires in northeast <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, but the forecast was for hot and dry weather over the weekend, and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said, `` All these fires are real worries because any one of them can blow up.'' Crews battling five forest fires in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s mountain ranges hoped to contain the blazes by today, but forest fire danger will remain high throughout the holiday weekend, they predicted. Despite tinder-dry conditions, this year's fires have been much smaller than last year's because there have n't been strong winds. <PERSON> Harley </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> warned, however, that more lightning and temperatures in the 90s in the mountains are expected during the Labor Day weekend, adding to the danger. In the Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness along the Montana-Wyoming border, crews had to be pulled back from a fire line Thursday along a flank of a 47,200-acre fire when the blaze flared up and destroyed portions of the line. `` The fire got rolling in there and it got too hot,'' said fire information officer <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Comstock </PERSON>. `` This is the fourth day we've built good line and had to back up and let it go. In <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, strong ridgetop winds near the Pineview Reservoir fanned a once-controlled fire into a 2,000-acre inferno threatening high-voltage lines that bring power to the Salt Lake-Ogden-Provo metropolitan area.
