<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s first legal privately owned newspaper in 26 years began publishing Friday, and it said it would present the `` true and unbiased news.'' In its four pages, the People's View printed photographs and accounts of demonstrations in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> against the authoritarian government, and of student protests last month outside the Burmese embassies in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. It also carried the full text of President <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>'s address to the nation Thursday in which he rejected calls for an interim government to lead <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> back to democracy, which ended with a military coup in 1962. <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> View </ORGANIZATION> said it would be enlarged and carry foreign news when conditions improved, and declared in its first editorial: `` Under the current conditions of scarcity of newsprint, ink and other materials, the first privately owned newspaper is published to cater to the people with true and unbiased news of the prevailing situation.'' It did not editorialize about the political turmoil in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. No price was printed on the front page, but People's View was selling for up to 34 cents, several times the cost of the generally distrusted government newspapers. The new morning paper's owner and publisher is <PERSON> Kyaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyein </PERSON> and the editor is Tun Tha, sports editor of the government-run newspaper <PERSON> Kyemon </PERSON>. People's View is licensed by the government but not controlled by it. <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>'s six other dailies, two in English four in <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION>, are owned by the government. Twenty-one privately owned newspapers were published in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> before the coup by Gen. <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON>, who nationalized all newspapers, radio stations and television stations. <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON>, vice chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, told the legislature Aug. 19 the government would permit privately run newspapers, journals and magazines so as to `` provide an opportunity to bring out the people's wants and desires and accurate news about what's happening at work places and in regions. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> assumed power the same day as the first civilian leader since Ne Win's military coup. Ne Win resigned late in July and was succeeded by <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, a hard-line former general, who was driven from office in 17 days by huge protests against 26 years of isolation and economic disaster. Employees of the government newspapers went on strike last month, demanding greater press freedom, and kept the newspapers off the streets for three days. They returned to work Aug. 28, saying they had been assured their demands would be met. Several unauthorized newspapers have appeared, poorly printed but selling for up to $ 1.
