<HEAD>Israeli Analysts Say Soviets Expanding Tartus-Arwad Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviets are expanding naval facilities in the <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Tartus </LOCATION> and the neighboring island of <LOCATION> Arwad </LOCATION> to counter the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presence in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, Israeli analysts said Friday. Soviet installations in <LOCATION> Tartus </LOCATION>, including submarine and surface ship maintenance facilities, constitute the largest Soviet naval base in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Dore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviv </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Jaffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Aharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Levran </PERSON>, editor of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Balance </ORGANIZATION> published this week by the center, said the facilities extend to <LOCATION> Arwad </LOCATION> island and include recreation facilities for Soviet crews. <PERSON> Gold </PERSON> said no declassified information was available on the current or planned size of the Soviet base, but that the general and continuing trend has been expansion since 1987. He said the Soviet navy's <ORGANIZATION> Mediterranean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> is using <LOCATION> Tartus </LOCATION>, about 200 miles north of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, because it is outside <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> territory and has good access to the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. The Soviets use other land installations in <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> for intelligence-gathering, Gold and <PERSON> Levran </PERSON> said in separate interviews. <PERSON> Gold </PERSON> said the main objective of the <LOCATION> Tartus </LOCATION> base expansion was to counter the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 6th Fleet presence in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has bases in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had to find new arrangements after <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION> shifted its alliance to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1961 and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> dropped its friendship treaty with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1976, he said. <PERSON> Gold </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Tartus </LOCATION> facility was important for prolonged deployment of Soviet attack submarines in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. The London-based <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>'s Defense Weekly in May called <LOCATION> Tartus </LOCATION> `` the primary maintenance facility for Soviet submarines operating in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Levran </PERSON> said the Soviets have been using <LOCATION> Tartus </LOCATION> for at least five years and that the base's expansion apparently was a price <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> had to pay for purchasing Soviet weapons. Despite the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s recent reluctance to supply <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> with advanced weapons systems, he said, `` <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> is still the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s strategic asset in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>.'' He said the base replaced the Soviet practice of using <ORGANIZATION> Mediterranean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> ships for maintenance. But he said the base was less important than the recently developed Soviet Far Eastern base in <LOCATION> Cam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.
