<HEAD>Singapore Parliamentary Elections At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Singapore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a look at Saturday's parliamentary elections:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 CANDIDATES: 87 for 42 seats in traditional single-member districts. Another 13 constituencies elect only three-member teams for a total of 81 seats in the unicameral legislature. They serve five-year terms.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 PARTIES: Only the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which has controlled this island republic since 1959 and won 11 seats unopposed on nomination day, is contesting all districts. The Workers' Party with 32 candidates and the <ORGANIZATION> Singapore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with 18 are the major opposition groups. Others are the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with 8, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> 5, <ORGANIZATION> Singapore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Malay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> 4, <ORGANIZATION> Singapore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> 3, and <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> 1. There are four independents.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 FORMER <LOCATION> PARLIAMENT </LOCATION>: Elected in December 1984, it had 79 seats, with the <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> winning 77, and one each going to the <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Singapore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. When it was dissolved on Aug. 17 the <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> had 76 seats, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> one and there were two vacancies.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 MAIN ISSUE: A plan to amend the Constitution to change the ceremonial presidency into an elected one with veto power over spending financial reserves and nominations to senior civil service and judicial positions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 COMPULSORY VOTING: 1.5 million eligible in the 70 contested districts. Voting hours 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. at 319 polling stations, with results from 12 counting centers expected about midnight.
</TEXT>
