<HEAD>Election Marks Generational Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Saturday's election in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> will pass the torch of leadership to a younger generation, but the man who has led this prosperous Asian city-state since 1959 is not expected to retire. The governing <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is expected to win the parliamentary election by a big margin. Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON>, who will be 65 on Sept. 16, is expected to step down in favor of First Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chok </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON>, 46. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who called the election `` truly a watershed,'' has been prime minister since 1959 and more than half of the 2.6 million people have known no other leader. He is to remain secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> and, although he has expressed disinterest, is still regarded as the most logical candidate to be the country's first elected president. `` Those who believe that when I have left the government as prime minister, that I have gone into permanent retirement, really should have their heads examined,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said recently. The proposed elected presidency remained the key issue as the nine-day campaign wound down Friday. It would replace the current appointed ceremonial post with a president holding veto power over spending the nation's ample financial reserves and nominations to senior civil service and judicial positions. Even the most optimistic of opposition leaders do not expect to be able to muster enough votes to form a government. The <ORGANIZATION> Singapore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> under <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> See </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON>, the only opposition member when the last <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> was dis