lly perceived to be efficient and relatively free of corruption. The recently enlarged unicameral <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> now has 81 seats, and the legislators serve five-year terms. The <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> already has 11 seats where it was running unopposed. The <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> needs to win at least 30 more seats to get a simple majority of 41 to form a new government and run the country for the eighth consecutive term since 1959. It faces 141 candidates from seven opposition parties and four independents. Opposition candidates numbered only 51 in the last election. There are 42 traditional single-member voting districts. But for the first time, each party competing in 13 constituencies had to nominate three candidates, at least one of them from a minority group. Voters select a team of three and each gets a separate vote in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s 2 million people are 76 percent ethnic Chinese, about 15 percent Malay and six percent Indians. Voting is compulsory for the 1.5 million eligible voters in the 70 contested districts. Voting hours Saturday are from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m., with results expected about midnight.
