<HEAD>New Rules Mean Simple `John Hancock' Isn't Enough For Check
Endorsement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `Only ``appropriate ...' to CLARIFY that
color restriction applies to banks, not customers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scrawling your <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> across the back of a paycheck may not be enough to get it cashed anymore, no matter how large your bank account or how well you know your teller. A new federal law guaranteeing customers faster access to their deposits includes little-known, uniform standards for endorsing checks. Under the regulations, which took effect Thursday, all endorsements must be within a 1 -LCB- - inch section along the edge of the back of the check so they do n't interfere with endorsements from the bank at which the check is deposited Only `` appropriate color ink,'' such as blue and black, may be used by banks for their endorsements, according to the regulations administered by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. Financial institutions say they have been training employees and mailing out brochures with diagrams to educate customers on the new standards. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON>, a senior vice president from <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said there have been few problems so far. `` I'm unaware of any excessive long lines,'' he said. `` -LRB- But -RRB- let's be honest, there's going to be an adjustment period. It's going to take time for everyone to understand and adjust to the rules. Some bank employees said privately they were bracing for a few initial headaches. Incorrect customer endorsements, they said, could delay check clearing and might affect subsequent transactions based on money derived from that check. `` It wo n't be the bank's problem; it's the customer's problem. But we'll be hearing about it,'' said one branch manager of a large New York-based bank. Stores also have had to adjust to the new guidelines. Many businesses routinely stamp the backs of checks with a lengthy list of identification items store clerks must obtain from customers. As a result, stores have had to buy new rubber stamps or reprogram cash registers to print within the smaller endorsement area. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has defended the new requirements as necessary to speed check-clearing so that bounced checks can be returned quickly to the institution where they were cashed. The new rules require financial institutions to give customers access to deposited funds within one, three or seven days, depending on the type of check. Consumer groups had complained that too many banks were holding funds for periods as long as two or three weeks before making the money available to the depositor, a practice that cost Americans millions of dollars in interest.
</TEXT>
