<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion rocked downtown <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION> just after the evening rush hour today, extensively damaging a clothing store and slightly injuring a black woman, police said. In other cities, a hand grenade was tossed at the home of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s leading mixed-race politician, and a bomb exploded in a post office, but no injuries were reported in those attacks. Glass and concrete littered one of <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>'s main streets following the 5:45 p.m. blast, witnesses said. The explosion occurred inside a street-level clothing store, causing major damage to the shop and two adjacent stores, witnesses said. The street was largely deserted at the time of the explosion, but had been full of traffic less than an hour earlier. Police initially said no one was hurt, but later said a black woman suffered minor injuries. The grenade attack in the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION> town of Uitenhage damaged a parked car but did not hit the house of Rev. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>. The mine exploded inside a package at the post office in <LOCATION> Stranderton </LOCATION>, southeast of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. No group immediately claimed responsibility for any of the attacks. More than 100 bombings have been reported in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> under the 26-month state of emergency. Police have blamed virtually all of the attacks on the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the main black group fighting to overthrow the white-dominated government. On Wednesday, a bombing destroyed a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> office building used by anti-apartheid groups and explosions Thursday in <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Two people were killed and 15 injured Thursday when a bomb went off at a hotel in <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and a mine exploded later alongside a railroad track near the city in the South African-ruled territory. No injuries were reported in the railroad bombing. Officials earlier had said two people were injured. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s chief representative in the territory, <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>, blamed the hotel bombing on pro-independence guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. But <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>, which began observing a voluntary cease-fire Thursday, denied the allegation and blamed it on `` <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s dirty tactics.'' Political and community leaders have expressed fears that the attacks signal an escalation of retaliatory attacks by anti-apartheid militants and by right-wing extremists. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> that controls the mixed-race chamber of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, was not at his home when the grenade exploded about 1:05 a.m., but two of his children were in the house. Anti-apartheid activists have criticized <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> for agreeing to mixed-race participation in the white-dominated Parliament, even though the black majority remains excluded. <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON> this year also defied President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> several times by pressing for the abolition of legally-enforced residential segregation. In what one newspaper called `` a humiliating defeat,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORG