<FIRST>r a AM-BloodBank     09-02 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blood Bank,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blood Center Chastised Over AIDS Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A blood center has been criticized by federal officials for distributing 22 units of blood before completely ensuring that they were not infected by the virus that causes AIDS, the center's director says. <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials inspected the <ORGANIZATION> Belle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bonfils </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in July and said the center failed to follow standard procedures by releasing blood that initially tested positive for AIDS and hepatitis, said center director Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bonfils </PERSON> supplies blood to regional hospitals. The blood, which went to about 45 people, later tested negative when new chemicals were used in followup tests, said <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. Blood center officials also retested all but two of the donors of the blood, and all had negative test results for AIDS and hepatitis, said <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. He said transfusion recipients were not contacted, because officials are confident they were not infected. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> said the 22 blood units tested positive for the usually fatal AIDS virus and hepatitis during one week in June. `` Ordinarily, we see maybe three to five test positive,'' he said. When any unit of blood tests positive, the center performs two additional tests, said <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. If both followup tests are negative, the blood is released. If one is positive, additional tests are done and the blood may be discarded, said <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. The 22 units of blood in question did not pass both tests the day after the initial tests read positive for AIDS and hepatitis. But <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> said laboratory technicians believed the tests were defective and they released the blood. `` This was a really unusual number, and the lab felt something was wrong with the test chemicals,'' the doctor said. `` New chemicals were used the following week, and on retesting all those units were negative'' for the diseases. `` Clearly this shows the tests were faulty,'' said <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. `` But ordinarily we would not use a unit when there is any question. ... It's not the safest thing to do.'' The center has instituted a policy requiring supervisors to approve all units of blood that test positive for AIDS, said <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. He said lab technicians had made those decisions previously.
