<HEAD>Toxic Waste Ship to Return to Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A West German freighter carrying 2,100 tons of toxic wastes will unload its cargo in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, government officials said Friday. The ship, the <PERSON> Karin </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>, was denied permission to dock in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. The wastes originally were shipped from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and dumped illegally in <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>. Environment Minister <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruffolo </PERSON> and Civil Defense Minister <PERSON> Vito </PERSON> <PERSON> Lattanzio </PERSON> said after a Cabinet meeting that the wastes probably will be unloaded at an unspecified Italian military port. The ship is anchored in international waters off the coast of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The wastes may have come from as many as 10 European countries, but they were shipped from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>'s military government seized an Italian ship, the Piave, last July to bolster its demand that <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> remove the wastes. The <PERSON> Karin </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON> was the first of two ships sent to pick up the wastes. It sailed from <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> on July 30. The second ship, The Deep Sea Carrier, sailed from <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> on Aug. 15 and reportedly is steaming off the coast of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. The Cabinet announcement did not mention the second ship. Officials have said they do n't know the precise chemical content of the cargo. But on Wednesday, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Smeraldi </PERSON>, a spokesman for the environmental group Friends of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, said its lab technicians in <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> found the drums contained PCBs and were highly flammable. PCBs, or polycholorinated biphenyls, can cause cancer and burns on contact. The plight of the <PERSON> Karin </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON> is similar to that of the <LOCATION> Zanoobia </LOCATION>, the Syrian freighter that was <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s first so-called ship of poison. It wandered the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> for four months with a cargo that had once been dumped illegally in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. That ship was finally given permission in June to unload its 12,000 drums of industrial waste in <LOCATION> Genoa </LOCATION>.
