<BYLINE>By PETER O'LOUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CULGOORA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first big radio telescope array in the <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION> began operating Friday, opening a new window on the little-explored southern sky. `` We'll be looking at the center of our galaxy because it passes right above our head in the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hemisphere </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Ekers </PERSON>, the director of the instrument named the <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> Telescope. `` Much of the galaxy and the nearest neighboring galaxy, the <ORGANIZATION> Magellanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cloud </ORGANIZATION> is not visible to observatories in the Northern Hemisphere.'' Ekers, who for seven years was director of the 27-dish, Very Large Array radio telescope in western <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, said the telescope will study black holes and pulsars. The new $ 40 million instrument located on the windswept plains of western <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>, consists of five new 72.6-foot dishes mounted on 1.86 miles of railroad track. An identical dish on a track 1.86 miles away will make the array equivalent to one dish with a diameter 3.72 miles. When linked to the exisiting 211-foot-dish at Parkes 241 miles to the south and others spread across the continent, the <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Telescope </LOCATION> can be extended like a zoom lens on a camera, to the equivalent of a dish 2,400 miles in diameter. The Commonwealth Scientific and <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, the government - funded research institution that designed the telescope, said the compact array of seven telescopes had an equivalent resolution to being able to read a telephone directory at a distance of 660 feet When linked to telescopes in space, it would be 10,000 times greater. `` The <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Telescope </LOCATION> is the state of the art in astronomical technology, it is one of the best telescopes in the world,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> told an audience of astronomers and scientists at the inaugural ceremony. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Laan </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, said: `` If <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> had n't built it, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION> would have had to do it in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>.'' `` We have the biggest optical telescopes in the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hemisphere </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Silla </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, but we had no major radio telescope array. World astronomy can not do without it,'' he said. `` This fills that gap and it puts <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> back in the top league of astronomy. Its the equivalent of winning the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Cup in yachting,'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Laan </PERSON> said
