<HEAD>Emperor Says He's in Good Health Despite Fever</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> took the unusual step Friday of assuring reporters that he was in good health following a fever earlier in the week that kept him in bed for two days. But Japanese reporters who attended the five-minute meeting with the world's longest reigning monarch said he looked frail and his cheeks were hollow. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, 87, underwent an intestinal bypass operation a year ago, and since then has limited his official duties. `` I'm completely recovered, so please do n't worry,'' the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> quoted him as telling reporters at the imperial villa in <LOCATION> Nasu </LOCATION>, northeast of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where he has been vacationing with Empress <PERSON> Nagako </PERSON>. The emperor remained in bed Monday and Tuesday with a cold and fever of about 99.5 degrees, an <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> official said. `` He seems to be in good condition now,'' the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. In a rare negative description of the emperor's health by the Japanese mass media, <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said he looked frail, his shoulders were sloping and he spoke in a weak voice.
