<HEAD>Dukakis Brings Back Former Aide, Who Promises Close Scrutiny Of
Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> welcomed former top aide <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> back to his presidential campaign Friday, nearly a year after <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> declared that <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> `` will not be back'' because of his role in torpedoing Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>'s bid for the Democratic nomination. The return of <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> as campaign vice chairman, announced jointly by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and his senior advisers in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, was widely seen as another signal that the Democratic nominee has decided to mount a more aggressive campaign at a time when Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has pulled even in most polls. `` Almost a year ago, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> made a very serious mistake,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> reporters. `` He's paid the price.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he was rehiring his longtime political alter-ego because he wanted to assemble `` the strongest team I possibly can'' for the final two months of the campaign. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>'s return had nothing to do with his recent decline in the polls. `` It's simply the fact we're looking at a little more than two months of what is going to be a very tough, very competitive campaign,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` It's going to be a battle royal for the presidency of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> chief of staff <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said the rehiring of <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> `` speaks for itself.'' <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, campaigning in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, said it was `` another sign that the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign is in serious trouble.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>'s involvement in the <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> incident `` should not obscure a long and well-deserved reputation for character and for integrity.'' In <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> received a thunderous ovation from <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign and state government loyalists when he walked into a news conference with campaign chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>'s replacement as campaign manager, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> directed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' gubernatorial comeback in 1982, served as statehouse chief of staff and was architect of the nominee's presidential campaign He resigned in September 1987 admitting that he circulated a videotape showing <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> using a British politician's rhetoric without attribution. News accounts about that incident and charges of plagiarism forced <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> to withdraw from the Democratic presidential contest. At first, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> denied that his campaign staff was responsible for the videotapes, but he later acknowledged that <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> was behind them. <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> and political director <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Tully </PERSON>, who helped <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> prepare the tapes, then resigned. `` What I did back on September was an error in judgment and I am sorry that it hurt Sen. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> and his family,'' <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> said Friday. <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> both spoke to <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> earlier Friday before his return to the campaign was announced, aides said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> `` could not have been more gracious.'' <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> dismissed suggestions that his return would give the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign an excuse to accuse <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of planning a `` sleaze'' campaign. That would be `` outrageous'' of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> people, he said. `` They certainly have a problem along those lines.'' Although he apologized to <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> said there was nothing `` unethical or illegal'' about distributing accurate videotapes showing the similarity of speeches by <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON>. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> issued a statement saying he was glad <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> had agreed that the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> senator `` never meant to mislead anyone.'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said he still supports <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for president. `` There are contrasts and weaknesses that are issues in this campaign,'' said <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>, who will take a leave of absence from his job with an advertising firm. `` I will not shy away from pointing those contrasts out.'' That promise drew applause from campaign workers who have complained that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his top aides had not counter-attacked vigorously enough when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> misprepresented <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' record. If nothing else, <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>'s return energized a campaign staff that has been sobered in recent weeks by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s surge in the polls. Many believe that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' failure to respond to the Republican nominee's salvos has cost the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor the momentum _ and the lead in the polls _ that he took from the Democratic National Convention. <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> said spoke to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on Tuesday and was asked if he would return. `` I said if he thought I could help, of course I'd do it,'' <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> said. `` Now we've got all of our best players on the field,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> issues adviser <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Herman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said he, <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> would report directly to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and that other campaign staff would continue to report to <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON>. Campaign aides insisted that the decision to rehire <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> was not a sign of dissatisfaction with <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON>'s performance, although several said her role in campaign strategy likely would be reduced somewhat. She put the best light on the announcement. `` Today, a family is reunited,'' she said, introducing <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> to reporters. `` There's nothing more special, nothing more satisfying, than reaching out to family. And to me, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> is family.'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> would bring `` additional strength, important political insight and wisdom to a very strong campaign team.''
