<HEAD>Seismic Station Records Tremors Twice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two tremors were recorded Friday at a seismic station here, aftershocks from a deadly earthquake last month which killed more than 1,000 people in <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, seismologists said. No damage or injuries were reported in the latest temblors. Seismologists said a tremor registering 4.8 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale occured at 3:45 a.m. and another, registering 5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, took place at 12:20 p.m. The epicentre of the tremors was in <LOCATION> Udayapur </LOCATION>, 35 miles north of the India-Nepal border, the seismologists said. The Richter scale measures the engery released by an earthquake according to the ground motion as recorded by seismographs. A reading of 6 means the earthquake can cause severe damage and a reading of 7 indicates a major earthquake. The earthquake Aug. 21 registered 6.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale.
