<HEAD>`Dance Ban' Attorney Seeks Clarification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 School officials in a small southwestern <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> town need more guidance before they can respond to a federal order striking down their ban on school-sponsored dancing, according to their attorney. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> ruled last month that the ban on dancing at <ORGANIZATION> Purdy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> was unconstitutional because it promoted the values of those who oppose dancing for religious reasons. The judge said it was not his role to order the district to hold dances, but he said the district could not enforce a no-dance rule that some believe to be a century old. `` Defendants respectfully submit that they do not understand what the court is ordering them to do or refrain from doing,'' wrote school district attorney <PERSON> Ransom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> in a brief filed Thursday. But lawyer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischaker </PERSON>, representing the 21 young people and parents who challenged the ban, said `` there's no question in my mind'' about the order. `` Any efforts by the school district to unreasonably prevent the students from having a dance would be in contempt of that order,'' <PERSON> Fleischaker </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fleischaker </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>' request for a clarification was `` typical of what's gone on all along here _ the school district has abandoned responsibility. They said, ` We ca n't allow dancing because of the rule.' Now they're saying, ` We do n't know what we have to do. Judge, you tell us what we have to do.' They've run for school board, let them use some responsibility.'' The <PERSON> Purdy </PERSON> school system, centered in a town of about 900 people 50 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, has about 520 pupils. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> did not address <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>' arguments at a hearing Friday, during which the judge considered the amount of attorney fees to be awarded the pro-dance lawyers. The judge said he would make his final ruling in the case by the end of next week.
