<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feuding Black Groups Sign Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rival black political groups signed an accord Friday to end what has been called the country's worst factional fighting this century in which more than 600 people have been killed in 20 months An explosion rocked downtown <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION> just after the evening rush hour, causing extensive damage to a clothing store and slightly injuring a black woman, police said. In other cities, a hand grenade was tossed at the home of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s leading mixed-race politician, and a bomb exploded in a post office. No injuries were reported in either attack. The agreement signed Friday sought to halt savage fighting in the <LOCATION> Natal </LOCATION> province between supporters of militant anti-apartheid organizations and members of <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION>, a more conservative group headed by <PERSON> Zulu </PERSON> leader <PERSON> Mangosuthu </PERSON> <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>. It was signed at a courthouse in the provincial capital, <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION>, by <PERSON> Inkatha </PERSON>'s secretary-general <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Dhlomo </PERSON> and by <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Naidoo </PERSON>, secretary - general of the militant <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions The labor federation has been allied with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a now-banned anti-apartheid coalition, in the feud against <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION>. The agreement condemns violence and establishes an adjudication board to review complaints of harassment or attacks. The board's members would be selected jointly by the two sides and would have disciplinary powers `` Each party recognizes the immediate necessity to make it abundantly clear to its members that <ORGANIZATION> COSATU </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Inkatha </ORGANIZATION> categorically condemn acts of intimidation, forced recruitment and violence,'' the agreement says. `` All political organizations have the right to exist and the <ORGANIZATION> democratic </ORGANIZATION> right to espouse their own particular viewpoint.'' <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Haysom </PERSON>, a lawyer for the labor federation who helped draft the accord, said both sides were cautious about their ability to convince rank-and-file supporters to honor the pact. `` The level of retribution and atrocious violence has made conditions almost impossible to exercise freedom of association,'' he said. <PERSON> Haysom </PERSON> said the adjudication board will be able to judge cases far more quickly than the courts can and will seek to gain the confidence of witnesses who have been fearful of making statements to police. Supreme Court Justice N.S. Page, who had asked the two sides to pursue an accord, said the courts were not abdicating their responsibilities but viewed the new board as a valuable additional tool to help stop the bloodshed. Most of the fighting has been in black townships around <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION>, although it has spread in recent months to townships near the larger port city of <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>. Many of the killings have been to avenge earlier killings. Both Inkatha, which claims 1.5 million members, and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> Front-labor federation alliance oppose the apartheid policies which enable 5 million whites to dominate 26 million blacks. But their strategies differ markedly. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a predominantly black coalition of some 600 groups, advocates economic sanctions, strikes, and other confrontational measures to bring about sweeping political and economic change. Inkatha opposes sanctions, avoids militant protest and advocates capitalism. Many militants view <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> as a government collaborator because he is chief minister of the <ORGANIZATION> KwaZulu </ORGANIZATION> homeland. However, <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> has rejected invitations by the government to join in negotiating reforms that would expand blacks' political role while leaving whites in ultimate control. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerschoff </PERSON>, a social worker in <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION> who has been involved in past reconciliation efforts, said the agreement was not the final step toward peace. Because of government bans and restrictions, he said in a telephone interview, `` it is extremely difficult for <ORGANIZATION> COSATU </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> UDF </ORGANIZATION> to communicate with grassroots people. This will have to be addressed.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> violence has distressed anti-apartheid campaigners elsewhere in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and sparked debate over whether black political groups could unite effectively to oppose the white-led government. Some commentators viewed the conflict as a harbinger of widespread infighting that might develop as black groups with different ideologies struggled for supremacy.
