TION> and southern <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bochkov </PERSON> said that more than 70 percent of Soviet national income is redistributed through the state budget. In line with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s drive to make each sector of the Soviet economy self-sufficient, <PERSON> Bochkov </PERSON> called for a decisive move to self-financing However, many Soviet factories and enterprises are still far from being able to stand on their own feet and meet expenses through their own revenues, and depend on periodic injections of government funds. <PERSON> Bochkov </PERSON> said Soviet warehouses and store shelves are now clogged with $ 746 billion in goods that no one wants to buy, and since the products remain unsold, the state earns no revenue from them. In his article, the economist also issued an indirect call for slimmed-down defense spending, saying: `` As in any sector of the expenditure of budgetary resources, in the military sector there is also the possibility of economy.'' The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s 1988 budget officially allocates $ 32 billion for defense, but Western analysts contend actual Soviet military spending is many times that figure.
