<HEAD>800,000-Ton Corn Sale Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought an additional 800,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn for delivery during the 1988-89 marketing year that began Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. Sale of 100,000 tons of corn was announced a day earlier, also for delivery in 1988-89. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 900,000 tons of corn would be about 35.5 million bushels. Corn prices have been averaging about $ 2.49 per bushel at the farm level, meaning that the two sales could have a farm value of around $ 88.4 million. There was no indication whether the new sales of corn would count under the current long-term grain supply agreement between the two countries or be carried forward separately in case a new pact is forthcoming. The current five-year pact is set to expire Sept. 30 and negotiators are currently trying to work out a new one, or at least an extension of the current agreement, to take effect Oct. 1. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Homann </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said it would be determined later how to count the latest corn sales, depending on the actual shipping dates and whether there is a new agreement. Regardless, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has already lived up to terms of the final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain. According to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. The Soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent. Prior to this week's sales, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had purchased 9.05 million tons of wheat and 5.17 million tons of corn for delivery in the fifth year of the agreement, plus 830,000 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal.
