<HEAD>Oral Roberts University Trims Medical Missionary Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oral <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> has reduced scholarship funds available to medical students and eliminated salaries for graduates who serve as medical missionaries for the university. The move is the latest modification in the medical missionary program that was the object of evangelist Oral <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>' widely publicized 1987 fund-raising effort, in which he claimed he might die if donors did n't come forward. Under the revised scholarship program, first-year medical students are no longer eligible for scholarship aid offered to those who plan to become missionaries. Other medical students who sign contracts promising to work as missionaries are to receive up to $ 20,000 in scholarship aid while they are in school, university officials said Thursday. Previously, participants were eligible for up to $ 24,000. In addition, the students will no longer be eligible for $ 22,000 salaries after graduation, when they do the missionary work. In January 1987, donations to the medical missionary scholarship program were falling when <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> issued a nationwide plea for $ 8 million. He said if he did not raise the money by April 1, 1987, God would `` call me home'' to heaven. Although Oral <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> officials announced the goal was met, <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> discontinued the scholarship program a year later amid much criticism. Three months after that, he reinstated it. Students who withdraw from the program may continue to attend Oral Roberts, said Dr. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, dean of the medical school. But they have to pay back whatever has been given them in scholarship money. The medical student scholarship program was begun as a pilot project for a few students in 1985. At the end of last semester, 105 students were receiving scholarships. The school now has 168 medical students enrolled, including 46 first-year students. The first-year students are not being offered scholarships, <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said, because officials want to get to know them during this school year to make sure they are truly called to be missionaries before offering aid.
