<HEAD>Exiled Chilean Artists Now Can Work at Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Critics accused President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> on Friday of lifting the exile ban only to gain votes, but whatever the motive, many Chilean artists and performers will be able to work in their own country. Gen. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who seeks to win eight more years in office as the sole candidate in a presidential referendum Oct. 5, announced Thursday that all 430 remaining political exiles may come home. One daughter of the late President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, overthrown in the coup led by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> in September 1973, already has returned and <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>'s widow and other daughter have said they will come back. Among other people affected is <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Littin </PERSON>, an acclaimed movie maker whose `` Acts of Marusia'' was nominated for an Academy Award as the best foreign film of 1985. <PERSON> Littin </PERSON> and thousands of other Chileans went into exile soon after the coup. It will not be <PERSON> Littin </PERSON>'s first return. He spent several weeks here in 1986 shooting scenes for a documentary on <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, but he was disguised, used an assumed name and posed as a member of an Italian television crew. That film, `` General Act of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>,'' is critical of the Pinochet militry regime and has been shown at several European movie festivals. An account of the secret visit was written later by Colombian author <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON>, a Nobel laureate and close friend of <LOCATION> Littin </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON> wrote that <PERSON> Littin </PERSON> visited several Chilean cities and on one occasion stood only a few yards from <LOCATION> Pinochet </LOCATION> while filming a ceremony. On Friday, the <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Epo