<HEAD>New Brazilian Constitution A Mixture of Nationalism And Liberalism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 4th pvs: The lawmakers completed... with
no further action needed for adoption.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers early Friday finished work on a new constitution that replaces the authoritarian charter drawn up two decades ago by military generals. The new constitution failed to make major social or economic changes, such as land reform and curbing the role of the military, but it legalizes strikes, abolishes censorship, strengthens <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>' rights and environmental laws, and lowers the voting age. `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is a new country. This constitution will protect the weak and punish those who abuse power,'' the constituent assembly's speaker <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON> <PERSON> Guimaraes </PERSON> said The lawmakers completed the document shortly before 2 a.m. They had begun work in February 1987, two years after civilian rule returned to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> after 23 years under the military. No further action is required for adoption of the constitution. The document has been sent to proofreaders and it will become effective Sept. 23. The 245-article constitution covers nearly every aspect of daily life: interest rates, education, health, divorce, <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>' rights, strikes and minimum wages. A first draft had reduced the military's role to basic keepers of the peace, but rumblings from the still-powerful, behind-the-scenes generals promoted the armed forces to `` defenders'' against foreign or national threats. The nationwide <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ruralist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> lobbied hard against land reform. Its leader, powerful landowner and chiropractor <PERSON> Ronaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Caiado </PERSON>, convinced thousands of farmers and rural workers that the constitution would expropriate `` productive land.'' Bowing to pressure, legislators excluded productive land from land reform, unless it produces marijuana. In a country where farms are the size of nations and 4 percent of the 143 million people own more than half the fertile land, very little land is expected to go to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s 12 million landless peasants under the constitution. President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, who came to power in 1985 in an indirect electoral college election, ardently fought against a parliamentary system of government and won a five-year term in office instead of four. Brazilians have n't voted for president since 1960 and most polls showed they wanted <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, a provincial politician closely linked to the military, out of office this year. Brazilians will vote for a new leader in November 1989. New envirnonmental laws are aimed at protecting <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> rainforest, randomly burned by the landless and speculators. Indians also gained new rights, including `` exclusive'' use of their land and resources. The constitution also: _ Lowers the voting age from 18 to 16 years of age. The only other country where 16 year olds can vote is <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. _ Legalizes strikes for all workers. Before, `` essential'' sectors of the labor force were not allowed to strike. _ Nationalizes mineral mining and gives foreign companies four years to hand over control to a Brazilian resident. _ Bans new oil risk contracts. _ Abolishes censorship of films, books and television. _ Abolishes the decree law, a powerful tool used by the president to bypass <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and push through legislation. _ Gives women 120-day maternity leaves and men five-day paternity leaves. The question Brazilians now must wrestle with is how to implement the constitution in a country with rampant corruption, runaway inflation and vast economic and social inequality. In 1993, Brazilians will vote on whether they prefer a monarch, prime minister or president to run the country.
</TEXT>
