<TEXT>
 A federal judge Friday reimposed potentially bankrupting fines against <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> for defying a court-ordered housing desegregation plan, then unsuccessfully tried to reach a settlement in informal discussions. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sand </PERSON>, who found the city guilty of racially segregating housing for 40 years, reinstated the fines which were upheld by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday night. Sand said the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision `` does not alleviate in any way, indeed one might agree it intensifies, the fiscal crisis that confronts the city of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>.'' He added that although the nation's highest court blocked fines and jail terms for four defiant city councilmen `` they -LRB- the councilmen -RRB- still have a responsibility to the citizens they represent who will bear the brunt of these fines.'' Because Monday, Labor Day, is a court holiday, Sand ordered the city to pay $ 192,000 on Tuesday. As previously promised by Sand, more than $ 85,000 of the money due will be earmarked for <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> public schools and to guarantee the payment of interest on city bonds. The balance of the $ 192,000 will go to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury and is non-refundable. Sand then called on lawyers for all parties to immediately meet with him privately `` to explore informally some ideas we have for a possible solution of this crisis.'' The talks ended after about an hour. `` It was not successful,'' Mayor <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasicsko </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sussman </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People, said there was no progress and called it a `` hostile discussion.'' `` I have n't changed my position. I will do what I have to do,'' said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON>, one of the councilman opposed to the desegregation plan. On Aug. 1, the council voted 4-3 against incentives to build 800 units of middle-income housing throughout the city as part of the desegregation plan ordered by Sand. The fine had started at $ 100 on Aug. 2 and doubled daily until it was stopped after a week pending appeals. The city has paid $ 12,700 and was to resume paying at $ 12,800 on Friday until the fine reaches $ 1 million a day and stays there, growing in million-dollar jumps. Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said he would direct the city's <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday to begin making the substantial reductions in city spending and services that will be required by Sand's order. The control board, which assumed management of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>' finances Aug. 9, passed a resolution the same day saying it would seek the criminal charges against the four councilmen if the fines were reinstated. The charges stem from violating the control board act _ a state law _ by jeopardizing the city's fiscal condition. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said last week he would initiate removal proceedings against the four councilmen if the fines were reimposed. However, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Fryer </PERSON> said Friday that for the time being, the governor would not attempt to oust the recalcitrant councilmen. The high court's ruling was `` raising more questions about removal than already existed and there were already many questions,'' <PERSON> Fryer </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled late Thursday night to stay a lower court ruling that upheld contempt citations against the four councilmen, who had been paying $ 500-a-day fines and would have been subject to imprisonment this weekend. The court `` has granted the stay for the four council members'' until they have had time to ask the court formally to fully review their cases, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON> said Thursday night. `` The application so far as the city of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> is concerned has been denied,'' she said. Even with the $ 1 million daily fine cap, <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, the state's fourth-largest city with a population of 200,000 people just north of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, would be bankrupt by November, officials said House said the entire court considered the applications, and Justices <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> filed a 12-page dissent. `` As the city repeatedly points out in its application, ` <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> is relatively unique in that most of the governmental power in the city is centralized in the legislative branch.' For this reason the city IS the council,'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> wrote in arguing that all the stays be denied. <PERSON> Wasicsko </PERSON>, who favors complying with Sand's housing desegregation order, said the decision troubled him. `` The treasury of the city is going to be exposed and the taxpayers of the city are going to feel the burden,'' he said. `` One thing it denies is the political martyrdom of the councilmen. They were slated to go to jail on Sunday. Their personal fines have ceased. But the city is going to plummet to bankruptcy. So their onus is their duty to the city.'' Two of the four, <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Longo </PERSON> and Vice Mayor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON>, called the decision a `` great victory.'' But Councilman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chema </PERSON>, another of the four, called the decision `` a big personal victory, but I have serious concerns about the city.'' `` It's kind of like being administered oxygen while someone strangles you,'' said <PERSON> Chema </PERSON>. `` The relief becomes moot if he decides to bankrupt the city in the interim,'' <PERSON> Longo </PERSON> said. The fourth councilman, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagan </PERSON>, called the decision `` unexpected'' and declined to comment further.
