<HEAD>Human Rights Advocate Finishes Term as US Ambassdaor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEDRO SERVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> on Friday finished his three-year assignment here during which he was accused of meddling in <LOCATION> Paragay </LOCATION>'s internal affairs and was once tear-gassed at a garden party. Before boarding the plane, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> acknowleged having contacts with people and organizations Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s government considers subversive, but added: `` We never aligned ourselves with any group.'' He said the goal of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy is `` that <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> continue being a stable country. ... Thinking of the future, five or 20 years after <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, is to think of a transition with someone who knows how to promote development and democracy and justice, without violence.'' <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, 75, seized power in 1954 and has ruled this landlocked <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nation since with the support of the army and the <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> party. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s replacement, <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Towell </PERSON>, is to arrive next week in <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>. The departing ambassador told foreign reporters: `` When I got here, it was taboo to talk of anyone replacing the president. Now, everything has changed. President <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, like all of us, is a little older and I see it as a good step that he himself talks about his succession.'' Relations between <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and the general's authoritarian government became uneasy soon after the ambassador arrived in November 1985. The 50-year-old career diplomat, whose parents were Calvinist missionaries, traveled through the country advocating human rights and meeting with opposition groups. He pressed for the reopening of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Color </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>'s biggest newspaper, which was closed in 1984 for printing articles the government considered subversive. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> also had asked the government to track down the source of a signal that jammed broadcasts by <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nanduti </ORGANIZATION>, the country's most popular station before it was forced off the air Allegations about his conduct ranged from interfering in domestic politics to conspiracy and subversion. Interior Minister <PERSON> Sabino </PERSON> <PERSON> Montanaro </PERSON> said last year <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> was close to being declared `` persona non grata.'' Police fired tear gas at a garden party given in his honor in February 1987, but <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> continued to press for human rights and speak his mind _ including a hint in February 1988 that government officials might be involved in drug trafficking.
