<HEAD>Judge Lifts Probation Term Requiring Birth Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BURT GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge Friday reversed her order that a teen-age mother who left her two sons alone in a sweltering apartment for three days, practice birth control throughout her child-bearing years, saying it was unenforceable. <ORGANIZATION> Maricopa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Budzyn </PERSON> had sentenced <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Forster </PERSON> on May 24 to lifetime probation with the birth-control stipulation. At a hearing earlier in the week, Ms. <PERSON> Budzyn </PERSON> refused to revoke the probation even though she learned that Mrs. <PERSON> Forster </PERSON>, 18, is pregnant with her fourth child. She said Mrs. <PERSON> Forster </PERSON>'s pregnancy did n't mean that the court's orders had been ignored, since no method of birth control is foolproof. Mrs. <PERSON> Forster </PERSON> pleaded guilty in April to two counts of attempted child abuse stemming from a May 1987 incident in which she left her two sons, <PERSON> William </PERSON>, 1 -LCB-, and <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, 6 months, alone in a <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> apartment for three days. Authorities said the apartment had no air conditioning, and both babies were dehydrated and near death when found. The judge said at <PERSON> Forster </PERSON>'s sentencing that the birth control stipulation was the only way to make sure Mrs. <PERSON> Forster </PERSON> did not have other children to abuse. Ms. <PERSON> Budzyn </PERSON>'s ruling Friday came on motions filed by defense attorney <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Forster </PERSON>'s public defender, and attorney <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, representing the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATI