<HEAD>First Day of Hunt Provides Victories, Defeats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf, `The first ...,' with number
of alligators taken the first night.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MH1, MH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEWISTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most alligator hunters were disappointed after the first day of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s month-long gator season, but by Friday morning some lucky ones bagged animals as long as nine feet. Thursday at sunset marked the beginning of the first legal alligator hunt in 26 years for the lucky _ or not-so-lucky _ 230 people granted permits to catch the reptiles with harpoons, nooses, crossbows and almost anything but a gun. The first night of the 30-day hunt netted about 130 alligators in 28 designated hunting areas across the state, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Game </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fresh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Thirty-eight were bagged in the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION>, while 36 were taken in the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Okeechobee </LOCATION> area, a spokesman said. Two novice hunters, <PERSON> David </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Navin </PERSON>, snaked through a <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> canal in the darkness looking for the red-reflecting eyes that give away the swimming reptiles, but the gators refused to cooperate. `` There's a few here, but they're not really doing what they're supposed to,'' chuckled <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Navin </PERSON> `` They're a little tougher than we thought.'' His brother <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> called their experience `` on-the-job training.'' To the north on <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Okeechobee </LOCATION>, one of the designated hunting areas, some gator pursuers reported better luck. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON>, 25, of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, the only northerner receiving a permit, bagged a nine-footer despite worrying beforehand that he might be unable to kill the animal even when he captured it. With gator hides selling for $ 42 a foot and meat running up to $ 6 a pound, <PERSON> Alpern </PERSON> and others persevered, though few expected to bag their 15-gator limit the first night. Hide and meat sales from a single alligator can total $ 300 to $ 500. `` We're having fun,'' said <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, an alligator hunter from <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. `` Where else but in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> can you go after a 500-pound animal that can kill you?'' Early success came to <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Donate </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and his guide, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Medore </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Clewiston </LOCATION>. They snagged a 8-foot-3-inch animal only 80 minutes after they started hunting on <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Okeechobee </LOCATION>. Once they got the gator reeled up to the side of the boat, they shot it with a `` bang stick,'' a firearm-like gadget that is allowed under the game commission rules. `` We blew one hell of a hole in his head,'' Donate said. `` It was exciting.'' He then taped the gator's mouth shut. `` It's scary putting that tape on his mouth, even with a hole in his head,'' he said. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Prater </PERSON>, who work for the city of <LOCATION> Pembroke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pines </LOCATION>' utilities department, bagged a 6-foot alligator and another that was 8 feet or longer. <PERSON> Prater </PERSON> showed how he hooked one just beside the alligator's left rear leg with a large hook on a heavy-duty saltwater fishing rod. He said fighting the gator when it was hooked was very difficult, and he snapped the heavy fiberglass rod. `` It was a deep-sea rod and it just plain snapped in two,'' he marveled. Alligator hunting was outlawed in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in 1962 because wildlife biologists feared overhunting of the ancient reptiles might threaten the survival of the alligator. A small alligator industry has built up in recent years because alligators have increasingly become problems by turning up in urban areas and pestering and occasionally killing humans or their pets. Estimates place the current number of alligators living in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> at 1 million, and game commission officials said they are now far from an `` endangered'' species.
