<HEAD>Ticket Sales Brisk For World-Record $52 Million Lotto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lottery machines spewed out tickets by the millions Friday as players scurried for a chance to win Saturday's world-record $ 52 million Lotto jackpot. Tickets were selling at a rate of about 265 per second, said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> lottery. For the day, 7.5 million tickets at $ 1 apiece had been sold by 5 p.m., compared to 4.9 million at the same time last Friday when the jackpot was $ 32 million. The jackpot has been climbing because no one has won since Aug. 6. Fridays are the lottery's second-biggest sales day. A full 50 percent of any week's sales are made on Saturdays through 10:30 p.m. when computerized ticket machines shut down for the 11 p.m. drawings. Last week some 32 million tickets were sold. This week, officials expected sales to hit 40 million. It took <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> only four months to break the world record for a Lotto prize, which <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> set in June with a $ 51.4 million prize that was shared by two winners. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> launched its Lotto game in April. In spite of the 14-million-to-one odds, the record-jackpot was attracting players from bordering states in large numbers, lottery officials said. Eight of the state's top 10 retailers, measured by ticket sales, are located in <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION> or northeast <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> counties bordering <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, neither of which has a legalized lottery, said <PERSON> George </PERSON>. `` We do know that our border retailers are very heavy,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON>. `` Any one of those retailers will tell you what the tags are on the cars in the parking lots.'' The lottery's telephone hotline has been receiving calls from out-of-state residents wanting to buy tickets without coming to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. But because <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> regulations prohibit the sale of the lottery tickets through the mail, people must visit <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to buy their tickets or have someone buy them. `` We've got so many people running in and out of here. I had somebody call at 6 o'clock this morning wanting to know if I was open,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McMurtray </PERSON>, manager of a convenience store and service station in <LOCATION> Bradfordville </LOCATION>, about eight miles south of the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> border. Lotto players select six numbers from one through 49, mark their selections on a computer card, which is read by a ticket machine. The $ 51.4 million <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> prize had been the world record, according to <ORGANIZATION> Terri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleur </ORGANIZATION>, a senior editor at Gaming and <ORGANIZATION> Wagering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION>, a monthly trade publication in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Valenza </PERSON>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION> Lottery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Players </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moorestown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, agreed with <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleur </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s `` El Gordo'' lottery gave away $ 56 million in 1983, but it was not a Lotto-style jackpot.
