ation and training, was unqualified to convene the court-martial because there was an appearance he had a personal interest in the outcome of the case. He contended <PERSON> Thunman </PERSON>'s interest stemmed from the adverse attention his command has received as a result of the death. <PERSON> Wynne </PERSON> argued against the motion, saying that extending <LOCATION> Wiltshire </LOCATION>'s theory up the chain of command would prohibit anyone, including the chief of naval operations, from convening a court-martial in such a high-visibility case. <PERSON> Thunman </PERSON> testified Wednesday that he had wanted to correct what he said were erroneous press reports that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> failed to begin investigating the case until receiving outside pressure from the victim's family, their congressman and the media. He also was concerned about initial reports released by <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman who incorrectly said the death was from natural causes.
