<HEAD>Come Festival Time, The Name's The Thing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What's in a name, you ask? At the <ORGANIZATION> Edinburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION>, a lot. With 913 shows on the unofficial Festival Fringe competing for theatergoers' time and money, participants found it's the name of the event, not necessarily the work itself, that often is the thing. `` If it's an unknown play, the name can make people look twice,'' playwright <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeal </PERSON> said of her show `` The Tainted Honey of Homicidal Bees,'' just one of numerous Fringe offerings whose title immediately catches the eye. Indeed, visitors to the 42nd Festival Fringe, which ended on Sept. 3, and which played alongside the Scottish capital's higher-profile mainstream cultural binge, are besieged by any number of suggestive, pun-filled or just plain odd titles chosen to make one event stand out from the next This year's entries ranged from take-offs on popular movies: There's both a `` Futile Attraction'' and a `` Fatal Distraction,'' based on the box-office hit `` Fatal Attraction,'' as well as a `` <ORGANIZATION> Jean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toilette </ORGANIZATION>,'' based on the critically acclaimed `` Jean de Florette.'' There also are Shakespearean send-ups such as `` Not Much of Ado'' and `` Jesus Christ! It's <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Caesar </PERSON>.'' Any title is permissible on the Fringe as long as it's not libelous. <PERSON> Trisha </PERSON> <PERSON> Emblem </PERSON>, the Fringe assistant administrator, defined a good title as one that's `` memorable, even if it's nothing witty.'' She cited `` The Life and <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hieronymus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bosch </ORGANIZATION>'' as a title that was effective because of its distinctiveness. Sometimes, people do n't realize how distinctive their title is. `` We did n't actually choose it to cause a stir,'' said <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>, co-director of `` Straight Laced, <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Orto </PERSON> n't, <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> Should n't, <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> Would n't, <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> Could n't, <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> Did n't,'' a satirical comedy that had this year's longest name. `` We all sat around and thought, ` OK, what are we going to call it?' And suddenly, it arrived,'' <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> recalled, aware that length has its disadvantages. `` We could n't fit the name on the tickets,'' she said, `` but it's on all the posters and leaflets.'' One playwright was worried his title was too distinctive. `` I have a feeling a lot of people are going to say it's strident,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Harries </PERSON> said of the title to his show `` Hold Your Horses, <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>,'' a comedy with music and dancing about one King Zog of <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION> But <PERSON> Harries </PERSON>, a 36 year-old marketing director who last wrote a Fringe play 10 years ago, stood by his choice: `` It's honest; it really does say what you need to know about the play. It's immediately arresting and surprising. And what if the title's good but the play itself is n't? All agreed that there's the rub. `` There has to be something behind a title, an interesting concept in the play itself,'' said <PERSON> Trisha </PERSON> <PERSON> Emblem </PERSON>. Speaking by telephone from his office in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Harries </PERSON> said, `` I shall be there -LRB- in <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> -RRB- every day ... talking to people to find out why they came to see my show.''
</TEXT>
