<HEAD>A Filmmaker of Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Having made films about political violence on three continents, Greek-born filmmaker <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON> now turns his attention to racial terrorism in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The movie is `` Betrayed,'' in which Debra Winger portrays an undercover <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent who becomes the lover of <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> farmer who leads a paramilitary white supremacy sect. The story begins with the murder of a controversial radio talk-show host and includes the robbing of banks to finance the movement. Once again a Costa-Gavras film has paralleled news events. His most famous films portrayed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> involvement in the overthrow of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s military regime -LRB- `` Missing'' -RRB-, and military despotism in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> -LRB- `` Z'' -RRB-. He has also dealt with torture in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in `` State of Siege,'' <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> Stalinism in `` The Confession'' and the Palestinian issue in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> with `` <PERSON> Hanna </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa-Gavras </PERSON>, who has lived in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for many years, is no stranger to controversy. He recently talked with accustomed frankness about his work and politics during a visit to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> for the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> opening of `` Betrayed.'' Q. Is there something unique about racism in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>? A. Here it's different. The expression of racism is probably much more violent. The ideology of racism is the same everywhere, unfortunately. Q. Did you do a lot of research for `` Betrayed''? A. Yes. The moment I started to do the movie, which means three years ago, I started doing research in the different fields. You find everything in television or in books or in newspaper interviews. It's extraordinary; everything is there. I saw hours of tapes. A lot of things happened during and after my research. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Beach </PERSON> happened while I was researching. Then the <PERSON> Bernhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> story. All those things are extraordinary. I think the last 10-15 years is a kind of wave of racism. -LRB- Costa-Gavras was referring to a Dec. 20, 1986, incident in the <LOCATION> Howard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, in which a group of young whites beat and chased some blacks, resulting in the death of one black. <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON>, who is white, was convicted in June 1987 of a weapons violation in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> subway shooting of four black youths he said he thought were going to rob him. -RRB- Q. Do you think racism has become more prevalent than before? A. Yes, I think so. I do not know the reasons. I try to understand why. I think it always was there, somehow. But people feel authorized to express themselves much more openly. Q. The most shocking scene in `` Betrayed'' is when the farmers, armed with automatic guns, stage a kind of nighttime foxhunt of a young black. Do you think that could happen in this country? A. No, I do n't have any direct evidence that it happened. What I'm trying to do there is make the scene as strong as possible, just to show how unbearable, how frightening can be racist murder. ... I do n't see much difference between killing a man on the street because he is black or has a different religion, or hunting him. I tried to dramatize how unacceptable that can be. Q. Why did you choose Debra Winger? <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> has the quality of being a strong person as a character and an excellent actress. She also has a very personal involvement in what is going on in the world. Those three elements are essential for someone to play that kind of role. Q. And <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON>? A. I like <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>'s cowboy style _ handsome and clean, he has that kind of face. And then it's like the moon: He has a dark side. All of us have our dark side. The important thing is how far we go with our dark side. Q. As an outsider, do you think you have a better view of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>? A. Maybe not better. Different, surely, because I have so much curiosity about your society. Everything that happens here has a direct effect on where we are coming from, the smaller countries of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, socially and artistically. We have a curiosity and also a tenderness about your country, because you have given us some many things: movies, theater, literature, music. These things we grew up on. Q. Your films always seem to have political overtones. Is this because of your particular psyche? A. I prefer to say `` ethical,'' a more hopeful view. But if we say `` political,'' I think all movies contain political meaning.... Every movie reflects the philosophy or the ethics of its authors Mine are no exception. Q. Do you deplore that outpouring of mindless violence and silly comedies that pour forth from the studios, especially in the summertime? A. Oh yes, yes. ... Let's take an example: the last `` Rambo.'' Everybody says, `` Let's be peaceful, let's try to understand each other, East-West.'' Then you have something that exploits passion and hate and all those things. But on the contrary, there is in the summertime some extraordinary qualities -LRB- in films -RRB-. I like very much the light movies. I like to go and have fun; it's very pleasant.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Sept. 9</NOTE>
