<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv06   09-02 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 06,0632</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tues., Sept. 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Worry The Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The big `` whew'' from the stock market last Friday came from evidence that inflationary pressures, and therefore interest rate increases, might possibly be easing. As has happened a hundred times in the past, Wall Street once again is mesmerized by inflation and interest-rate possibilities, and it reacts almost instantly to any news on the subject. A high or rising level of interest rates is of special importance to the stock market for at least two reasons: _ First, it is generally agreed that the stock market collapse of last October was triggered, at least in part, by rates rising to levels that made debt securities more rewarding than stocks _ Next, high or rising interest rates become an important factor in the cost of doing business, as well as a disincentive to market expansion at all levels from consumers to manufacturers Another reason might be added: The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has been watching job figures for a clue to inflation. Strong job figures might convince it to raise rates; a weaker job market would mean an easing of pressure. After viewing the figures, Wall Street concluded that the inflation threat might not be as bad as feared, and that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> would have less reason to push up interest rates. But the the threat is not over, and <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> <PERSON> Steet </PERSON> will continue to focus on borrowing costs and inflation. <ORGANIZATION> Wright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> presents the case: At current interest-rate levels, says <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, which advises on billions of dollars of investment funds, the possibility of new lows in stock prices _ lower than those of last October _ can not be dismissed. It points out that short-term interest rates are now more than 1 percentage point higher than they were one year ago at the stock market peak, while long-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> yields are around one-half percentage point higher. In fact, high-quality corporate bonds offer a return nearly 2 percentage points higher than that available on stocks, a situation that is out of whack with recent history. Over the past 20 years, stock earnings yields have averaged the same as long-term bond yields. Prior to 1984, says <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, bond yields as high as today's would have precluded a stock price-earnings ratio of more than 10. Thus, says <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, `` the current stock market price-earnings multiple of 12, while only average for the postwar period, may yet prove to be excessive in today's environment.'' Is the obsession with interest rates overdone? Does it ignore positive factors? Perhaps. Investor confidence could be supported by other aspects of the economy that show it to be stronger than a year ago, despite its advanced age. Corporate earnings are setting records. Price-earnings ratios have shrunk. Corporate takeover activities continue to remove stock from the market, thus creating a relative shortage of equities. And investor psychology is much healthier. A year ago, you may recall, investors floated on a cloud of euphoria and cared little for such fundamental considerations as real value. Now they fear the market; they study fundamentals, and they do n't take chances. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> agrees that these are indeed encouraging signs. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and a host of other analysts wonder if those interest rates still might not knock prices down as they did last year. So long as the threat exists, says <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, the bull market will have to wait. When will it come? You can be confident, it concludes, that a new bull market will get under way next year. Which means, in effect, that those interest-rate worries will have abated.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues., Sept. 6.</NOTE>
