<TEXT>
 The nation's largest general retailers were unable to break out of their 18-month slump in August as weather conditions and continuing problems in apparel lines depressed sales for yet another month. `` We were looking for a pickup that would hopefully continue through September and October,'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wintzer </PERSON>, a retail analyst for <PERSON> Alex </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday after the retailers announced their August sales figures. `` Some of the companies did worse in August than they did in June and July,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Labor costs rose, productivity fell and workers, despite higher wages, lost some of their purchasing power in the second quarter, the government has reported. In revised figures for April through June, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that the efficiency of non-farm businesses in churning out goods and services dropped at an annual rate of 1.4 percent, its first quarterly decline since 1986. Labor costs shot up at an annual rate of 5.7 percent, the biggest increase since 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Construction spending in July posted its sharpest increase in four months, but only partly recovered from a June slump, the government reports. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that building activity rose 1.2 percent to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of $ 401.0 billion in July, following a revised 1.5 percent drop in the previous month. The June figure was originally estimated as a slight 0.1 percent gain.
