<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices have responded negatively to a report of more overproduction by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, contracts for October delivery of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, fell 10 cents per barrel to close at $ 15.08 Thursday. Other contract months also dropped. Contracts for refined petroleum products finished mixed. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery rose 0.36 cent to finish at 44.71 a gallon. The September gasoline contract fell 1.49 cents Wednesday, the last trading day before the contract expired. Contracts for other months mostly were lower. Wholesale heating oil for October rose 0.14 cent to 43.46 cents a gallon while other contract months were mixed. Analysts said the strength in gasoline and heating oil prevented further declines in crude oil. They attributed the recent gains in refined products to poor refinery economics. Outdated equipment, for example, has lowered refinery capacity, keeping supply and demand nearly equal, they said. `` Refining capacity has been pared down to the point where refiners are having problems just keeping up with day to day demand,'' said <PERSON> Jayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, a commodity oil broker with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts said crude oil recovered from midday lows in response to reports that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> would exceed its production quota set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries In recent days, oil futures prices weakened after reports that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s 13 member nations were exceeding their collective quotas by more than 3 million barrels. `` All this overproduction in a market where demand factors have n't been substantial tends to be a price weakening factor and the market goes down,'' Ms. <PERSON> Ball </PERSON> said. `` <LOCATION> UAE </LOCATION> claims it's going to have production up to 1.9 million barrels per day, more than double its quota, which is about 990,000 barrels.'' Ongoing uncertainty about developments between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> also softened crude prices Thursday, traders said.
