 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has fired its longtime ad agency, which created the memorable ad campaigns showing a Charlie Chaplin-like character making his chaotic business run smoothly with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> products. The computer giant ended a three-month review of its advertising agencies by selecting <PERSON> Lintas </PERSON>: <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>, a unit of the <ORGANIZATION> Interpublic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Rich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> advertising assignment. The decision was the latest blow to its long-time agency, <ORGANIZATION> Lord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Einstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is losing its biggest client and has been wracked by internal turmoil for much of the year. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> reportedly spends more than $ 100 million a year on advertising. accounting for about half of Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>'s estimated $ 200 million in billings. Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>, which had competed to keep the account and expected to retain at least some of it, has worked for <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> since 1979, creating the Chaplinesque ads and, more recently, a series of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> ads reuniting the former stars of the television show `` M-A-S-H.'' <PERSON> Lintas </PERSON> is best known for its Cover Girl, <ORGANIZATION> Diet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> and Chevrolet ads, while <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON