TION> and the new agency and its leaders. In early June, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said it would review its agency requirements and advertising direction and invited a limited number of agencies to compete for the assignment, including both Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> and the breakaway agency, Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> & amp; Partners. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Theo </PERSON> <PERSON> Chisholm </PERSON> said the company heard presentations from six agencies. In addition to <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>, Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> and the two winners, they were <ORGANIZATION> D'Arcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Masius </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Bowles </PERSON> and Grey Advertising. In announcing its decision, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> declined to say how much it spends on advertising or how that spending will be split between the agencies. It said <PERSON> Lintas </PERSON> will be responsible for <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> desktop products, including the Personal System-2 line of personal computers, while <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greene </ORGANIZATION> will do corporate advertising as well as `` marketing image advertising and solutions advertising programs.'' At Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>, Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said he was disappointed but added, `` We never expected any <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> business when we left there.''
