<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather, Fashion Problems Blamed For August Slump</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's largest general retailers still are waiting for business to improve after continuing problems in apparel lines and unusually hot weather depressed sales again during August. `` It is not encouraging as a harbinger of what back-to-school and fall is going to look like,'' <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ronning </PERSON>, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harriman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said after reviewing sales results announced Thursday by storeowners. `` Some of the companies did worse in August than they did in June and July,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wintzer </PERSON>, an analyst with <PERSON> Alex </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. Several analysts blamed the August slump on the abnormally hot weather parts of the country suffered through last month. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Feiner </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the underlying sluggish trend in consumer spending _ which began in February 1987 _ also remained in place. Retail sales have been a soft spot in an otherwise strong economy. Consumer spending, which also includes outlays for food, medical care, autos, utilities, transportation and other necessities, is closely watched because it accounts for two-thirds of the gross national product. Some analysts dismissed the weather as a factor. <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, noted sales were disappointing on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> despite more normal temperatures there. <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON> said women are still disenchanted with retailers' fashion lines It was a year ago, in August 1987, that apparel retailers fell into a slide as women refused to buy shorter skirts and clothes they perceived as boring. `` A lot of retailers are pushing back their expectations for a good pickup in business until October,'' <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said it was too early to get a good reading on how well the new apparel lines are faring, but he said `` it appears as if some of the new fashion is better than it was last year.'' <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> said some stores have reported a pickup in business this week. Those sales will be reflected in retailers' September sales figures. Several companies recorded sales increases under 3 percent, meaning the stores were losing ground to inflation, which has run at an annual rate of 4.5 percent so far this year. The nation's largest retailer, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said its overall sales rose 6.3 percent from August 1987 levels, and its sales for the first 30 weeks of the fiscal year increased 5.5 percent from the same period a year earlier. Sales from <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> stores open at least a year _ known in the trade as same-store sales _ were up 1.3 percent last month and 2 percent for the year to date. Retailers and industry analysts believe same-store sales are a more accurate yardstick of a company's performance than figures which include sales from new stores. However, not all retailers report both their overall and same-store results. K mart said its sales rose 6.4 percent in August, and 5.4 percent for the year so far. The retailer's same-store sales rose 2.2 percent for the month and 1.9 percent year-to-date. <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its sales rose 24 percent overall last month, and have risen 30 percent so far this year. Its same-store sales were up 8 percent in August, and have risen 12 percent during the first seven months. <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> suffered a 2.6 percent drop in overall sales last month, while sales for the year so far were up 1.8 percent Same-store sales were down 3.4 percent last month while rising 0.7 percent for the year so far. <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 15 percent last month and 17.3 percent year-to-date. Same-store sales rose 1.7 percent in August and 1.5 percent for the first 30 weeks. May <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had a 19.6 percent jump in overall sales in August while year-to-date sales improved 13 percent. May's same-store sales were up 1.5 percent last month, and 1.3 percent for the year so far F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported a 12 percent increase in August sales, and an 11.9 percent rise for the first 30 weeks. <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its August sales were up 4.7 percent, while year-to-date sales rose 3 percent. The results were from general merchandise and apparel retailers. Unlike monthly retail sales figures released by the federal government, they do not include sales at auto dealers, supermarkets or restaurants.
