<SECOND>PM-Detroit Newspapers,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit JOA `Blueprint' for Gannett Expansion, Arkansas Newspaper
Alleges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A partial merger between the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> would mean trouble for the 25 other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities that still have competing newspapers, according to an <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> newspaper. The <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> Democrat of Little Rock filed a legal brief Thursday supporting efforts to block a proposed joint operating agreement between the News, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> The Democrat's main competitor is the <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION>, which is owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest newspaper chain. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> bought the <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> in 1986, the same year it acquired the News. Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> approved the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> on Aug. 8, shortly before leaving office. Court challenges followed, and the partial merger was delayed at least until next week, when it is to be reviewed by a federal judge in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` A decision approving the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> in this case would be a decision providing a blueprint for the elimination of competition in the remaining 25 cities with two newspapers,'' the Democrat's attorneys said. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision, in designating the Free Press a failing newspaper, ignored evidence that the newspaper's losses resulted from strategic decisions rather than market economics, the brief said. The Democrat asked the court `` to rule that a newspaper is not failing when its losses are the result of predation.'' The Democrat's brief said <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> operated both the News and the <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> at substantial losses in order to force smaller competitors to incur more painful losses. `` <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>'s strategy in acquiring the newspapers in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> was not to operate either profitably in a competitive market, but was instead to eliminate competition either by destroying its rival or by forcing its rival into a joint operating arrangement,'' the brief said. Six days after <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> approved the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> lowered subscription prices to 85 cents per week from $ 1.98 per week, the brief said. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> said the company would not comment immediately on the Democrat's allegations. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON>, publisher of the <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> agreement `` has nothing to do with us at all here at the Gazette.'' `` Number one, this price reduction was on the drawing board long before we knew anything about the outcome of the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> situation in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Number two, we're not trying to put them out of business. `` If you will look at the things we have done, it's just to match them _ free classifieds, we matched them with free classifieds. As far as circulation pricing, all we've been doing is matching what they've already been doing.'' The <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> agreement would merge News and Free Press production and business operations while keeping separate the newspapers' news and editorial departments. Profits and losses would be shared equally by the newspapers after the first five years of the 100-year agreement. The newspapers sought exemption from federal antitrust laws under the Newspaper Preservation Act, which allows such partial mergers when one of the newspapers is declared in danger of failing.
