<HEAD>Subroto Calls For Revamped OPEC Production Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto as one word is correct</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> Friday after visits to <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, where he apparently failed to settle the problem of setting oil output levels for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. In arrival statements, <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> indicated that he saw a solution only through a revamped production policy for the entire 13-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>'s talks in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> this week reportedly focused on the question of whether <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> should be allowed to increase its oil production quota to parity with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> quoted him as saying it was `` necessary that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> member states look into this problem -LRB- <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> output -RRB- within the framework of the basic issue from which <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> suffers ... overproduction by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> member states beyond the 15.06 million barrels daily ceiling.'' <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has refused to adhere to its quota of 1.54 million barrels a day, demanding parity with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s 2.369 million. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s unrestrained current output is estimated at 2.8 million barrels a day KUNA said <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> indicated the Iraq-Iran production controversy `` can not be solved separately from the rest of the pending issues related to <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production.'' Among the issues <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> is discussing during his current tour of <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> nations is the production level of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>, which he visited on an earlier tour and which currently is estimated to be producing at least twice its allotted quota. The U.A.E. announced its quota should be 1.5 million barrels a day instead of its alloted 948,000. Since late 1986, the cartel has slashed its aggregate output by more than 3 million barrels per day to try to stabilize nosediving prices around an $ 18-a-barrel benchmark. But quota violations by member states has made the target price elusive. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s current output is about 20 million barrels although the official overall ceiling set by the cartel is 15.06 million, excluding <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> last week on his way to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> said he believed it was reasonable that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> should have equal quotas of 2.3 million barrels a day. His statements to KUNA here confirmed he had made no headway so far. But he was quoted as saying `` we have not yet despaired and we still have a number of proposals in this connection.'' <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> said he discussed with Iraqi and Iranian officials `` the future level of output for each of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>,'' KUNA reported. He could not predict when a settlement was possible and said a single visit to each capital `` is difficult for reaching a solution.'' In <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> earlier in the day, <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> declined to comment to reporters on the result of his talks there. Iraqi officials described the talks as `` satisfactory.'' The official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said only that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s oil minister, <PERSON> Issam </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul-Rahim </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Chalabi </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> discussed recent developments in the oil market.
