<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Engineer's Suits Against Morton Thiokol</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with formal ruling filed; ADDS detail and
EDITS throughout to conform; ADDS byline; No pickup; Also moved on
general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge today dismissed two lawsuits seeking $ 3 billion from space shuttle rocket-maker <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> by a former company engineer who warned against the ill-fated 1986 Challenger launch. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Winder </PERSON> granted <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>'s request for dismissal of the suits filed by <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>, who left the company in July 1986, citing physical ailments and alleged mental torment Telephone calls to <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> home were not immediately returned. In his decision, <PERSON> Winder </PERSON> dismissed most counts in <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>'s suits with prejudice, meaning they can not be refiled But the judge said he would dismiss two counts of one suit, which deal with allegations of defamation and conspiracy, without prejudice. In one suit, <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> sought $ 1 billion for the deaths of the seven astronauts killed when Challenger exploded on Jan. 28, 1986, and $ 1 million in compensatory damages for <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>'s health and career. <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> claimed <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> impugned his professional reputation after he and other engineers testified before a presidential commission investigating the disaster that they had warned against the launch. His other lawsuit, filed under the False Claims Act on behalf of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxpayers, sought $ 2.075 billion and alleged that <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> knowingly provided <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> with defective solid rocket motors. <PERSON> Winder </PERSON> ruled that `` the ` conspiracy' alleged in the complaint is not of a nature to support an action for damages on the part of <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>. ... Neither the conspiracy itself nor the overt acts allegedly done in furtherance of it were directed toward <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>.'' The judge wrote that `` to suggest that the recommendation or the launch were acts directed toward and for the purpose of injuring <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> is ridiculous.'' `` Furthermore, for a reasonable person to know that <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> might suffer emotional injury as a result of the launch would include the requirement that the person know that the launch would end in disaster,'' <PERSON> Winder </PERSON> added. `` The dismissal of these two suits completely vindicates <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON>. `` We are very happy to have this situation behind us.'' Company attorneys had argued that <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>'s contention that he was defamed was based on office chatter. `` It is just workplace-related talk that goes on all the time,'' attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> told the judge at a hearing in February. However, <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, accused company officials of launching a campaign to defame the engineer through pamphlets and interviews. `` This is not a disgruntled person,'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> argued. `` This is an engineer who stood up and risked his career and hurt his health because he had this alternate view.'' In a May interview, <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> said it was only after two years of therapy and `` the positive catharsis'' of lecturing on the disaster that he was able to stop blaming himself for the destruction of the shuttle and deaths of its astronauts. `` For a long time, I bore the burden of guilt because I had n't done more to stop it,'' he said `` But I've resolved it now. I did everything I could.'' <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> and several other <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> engineers argued the night before the launch that temperatures of 53 degrees or less could cause a rocket joint seal to fail. But after a second caucus with <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials, <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> said, company managers `` perceived pressure from <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. ... There was no other justification for the launch. I felt the pressure, others felt the pressure.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which investigated the disaster, blamed the tragedy on a leaking joint seal that allowed superhot gases to escape and ignite the shuttle's external fuel tank. Investigators said the cold had weakened the seal. <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> took disability leave in July 1986, and left the company for good two months later. This year, he won the Scientific Freedom and Responsibility Award from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
