<HEAD>Productivity Report Indicates Squeeze In Economy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with latest stock and bond
prices; NYSE collar being triggered; picks up 5th graf pvs, The
Labor ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock and bond markets rallied powerfully today after the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment rate rose to 5.6 percent in August, a figure that eased concerns the economy was growing too briskly. The news that more Americans were out of work cheered up investors who were worried that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would have to raise interest rates to stave off inflation. Bond prices staged their biggest rally of the year, driving yields back down to the levels of early August. The yield on the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s benchmark 30-year bond plunged to 9.03 percent from 9.30 percent late Thursday. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 53.34 points to 2,055.65 by 1:30 p.m. EDT. The Dow Jones average's rise triggered a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> prohibition on member firms' use of <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> automated systems to perform a form of program trading known as index arbitrage. The prohibition kicks in when the index rises or falls more than 50 points. The dollar fell slightly against most major currencies as investors decided that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates would drop and make dollar-denominated securities less attractive to global investors. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the number of jobless Americans jumped by 226,000 in August to 6,851,000, as four months of hiring booms in factories and retail stores screeched to a halt. The August figure was 0.2 percentage point higher than July's civilian jobless rate of 5.4 percent, which was up 0.1 percent from June's 14-year low of 5.3 percent A separate survey of business payrolls, which many economists consider a more reliable indicator of the economy's health, showed 219,000 new jobs in August, well below the 400,000 average monthly increase in June and July. Today's unemployment data followed another government report showing the first quarterly decline in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> labor productivity since 1986. Analysts said the report indicated that hard-pressed businesses were being forced to hire less-skilled workers to fill job openings. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that the labor productivity of non-farm businesses fell 1.4 percent in the April-June period, less than the originally reported 1.7 percent decline. The report was roughly in line with expectations and did not have a large effect on the financial markets. Stock prices fell Thursday in sympathy with previous declines in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 29.34 points to 2,002.31. Other reports Thursday took some of the edge off fears of inflation and rising interest rates. August sales figures indicated the nation's largest general retailers were unable to escape their 18-month-old slump as weather and continuing problems in apparel lines kept customers away. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said construction spending rose 1.2 percent in July after slumping in June. On productivity, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> released revised figures showing productivity fell at an annual rate of 1.4 percent in the April-June period. The statistic measures the output per hour of labor for non-farm businesses. Labor costs shot up at a 5.7 percent annual rate _ the biggest increase since 1986 _ reflecting the productivity declines and wage and benefit increases averaging 4.2 percent annually. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Renfro </PERSON> of Alphametrics, an economic forecasting firm in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said the figures indicate that an `` inflationary head of steam is building.'' Economic output in the second quarter rose 3.3 percent, but to achieve the increased output, businesses had to raise the number of hours worked by their employees by 6.6 percent. Analysts said the increase in hours and consequent decrease in productivity reflects a hiring boom in which employers at a time of decade-low unemployment are relying more on less-skilled workers.
</TEXT>
