<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell against major currencies in European trading Friday after the announcement of slightly higher-than-expected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> August unemployment data. Gold prices also fell. Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar dropped sharply against the West German mark after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement that the unemployment rate had risen to 5.6 percent from 5.4 percent in July. Most traders had expected the unemployment rate to have remained at about the same levels as July, they said. One trader at a German bank in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> said the unemployment data accelerated an already noticeable downward trend in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency because the data suggested the American economy is slowing down, dampening expectations that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would increase interest rates in the near future. However, trading generally was quiet Friday, with many market participants confused about the market outlook and unwilling to take positions before the upcoming three-day Labor Day weekend in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.05 yen to a closing 136.75 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 137.65 yen. Other late dollar rates, compared with late Thursday: 1.8665 West German marks, down from 1.8795 1.5725 Swiss francs, down from 1.5835; 6.3365 French francs, down from 6.3780; 2.1050 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1205; 1,388.50 Italian lire, down from 1,398.50; 1.2362 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2370. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fetched $ 1.6755, compared with $ 1.6730 Thursday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 429.40 a troy ounce and at midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 428.95. Late Friday, gold fell to $ 427.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 428, down from $ 430.50 late Thursday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.26 to close at $ 431.35. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Friday at a bid price of $ 6.52 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.58 Thursday.
