<HEAD>Unemployment Rate Rose to 5.6 Percent in August</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 7-9, White House spokesman, with comment; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's unemployment rate rose to 5.6 percent in August as four months of hiring booms on factory assembly lines and in retail stores came to an abrupt halt, the government said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the number of jobless Americans jumped by 226,000 to 6,851,000 in August while the number of those with jobs rose by only 121,000 to 115,180,000. The 0.2 percentage point increase from July's civilian jobless rate of 5.4 percent followed a 0.1 percent rise from June's 14-year low of 5.3 percent. The report sparked a rally on Wall Street. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks climbed sharply in early trading as investors apparently viewed the unemployment rise as reducing upward pressure on interest rates and inflation. Most of the increased joblessness was suffered by adult men, with their unemployment rate rising 0.4 percentage points to 4.9 percent. The jobless rate among adult women, meanwhile, fell from 5.1 percent to 4.8 percent, the A separate survey of business payrolls _ which many economists consider a more reliable indicator of the economy's health _ showed 219,000 new jobs in August, well below the 400,000 average monthly increase in June and July.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. White House spokesman <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> with the vacationing president, called the report `` good news.'' `` The continued strong gains in August payroll employment confirm that the longest peacetime expansion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history continued through its 69th month,'' the spokesman said. Despite the increase in unemployment, <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said the administration was cheered by `` the good numbers underneath the overall numbers,'' such as in the jobless rate for women. The last time the civilian unemployment rate was at 5.6 percent was in May. The goods-producing side of the economy lost jobs for the first time since last January, with employment in manufacturing dropping by 5,000 after a 70,000 jump in July. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said small employment gains in printing and publishing and export-related industries such as machinery and electrical equipment were more than offset by 9,000 job losses in textile and apparel plants and smaller declines in several other manufacturing industries. Employment in oil and gas drilling also declined slightly, but it rose a minuscule 3,000 jobs in construction. On the services side of the economy, large monthly increases in retail trade hiring _ 80,000 in July alone _ slowed to just 23,000 new jobs last month, virtually all in grocery stores. Other recent high-growth job areas also slowed. Business services such as temporary help firms added just 16,000 new workers, compared with average monthly increases of 60,000 through the spring and early summer. New employment in health services, which the government predicts will be the largest area of job growth in the 1990s as the Baby Boom population ages, slowed to 22,000 in August. It also had been rising an average 30,000 a month in the past year. `` The labor market showed less strength in August than earlier in the year,'' said Labor Statistics Commissioner <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Norwood </PERSON>. `` Looked at over a somewhat longer period, however, the rate has hovered in the 5.3 percent to 5.6 percent range since last March and is 0.4 percentage point below the leval a year ago.'' Ms. <PERSON> Norwood </PERSON> said one encouraging sign was that the number of people working part-time involuntarily because they could not find full-time jobs `` returned to the bottom of the 5.2 million to 5.6 million range within which it has been fluctuating for more than a year.'' `` The proportion of working-age persons holding jobs remained at its record level of 62.3 percent,'' Ms. <PERSON> Norwood </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Other data in the report, however, suggested that the economy might be slowing. The average workweek declined by 20 minutes to 34.6 hours and manufacturing overtime fell by 0.1 hours to 3.8 hours a week on average. That sent weekly earnings down nearly a full percentage point as average hourly wages for non-supervisory workers held steady at $ 9.24. In the past 12 months, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said, wages have risen an average of only 3.1 percent, decreasing the buying power of workers, after taking inflation into account, by half a percent. A separate calculation that includes the 1.7 million uniformed armed forces in the job market showed a jobless rate of 5.5 percent last month, up from 5.4 percent in July. The government offered this other figures on unemployment in August: Whites, 4.9 percent, up from 4.7 percent in July. Blacks, 11.3 percent, down from 11.4 percent. Hispanics, 8.4 percent, up from 8 percent. Teen-agers, 15.8 percent, up from 15.2 percent. Black teen-gers, 15.8 percent, up from 15.2 percent. Private analysts had anticipated the overall jobless rate might rise prior to today's report. `` I think we're going to be stuck near 5.5 percent for the rest of the year,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinner </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, economic consulting firm. `` Employment is not going to fall; it's just not going to rise as fast as it has been.'' <PERSON> Brinner </PERSON>, like other economists, believes too many people, many of them with only marginal skills, have been hired in recent months in relation to the rate of economic growth. `` We may be at the point where we have absorbed most of labor's skilled capacity,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Renfro </PERSON>, chief economist for the forecasting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Alphametrics </ORGANIZATION>, also of <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON> `` Anything less than an uptick in the jobless rate will be a real danger sign that the economy is overheating.'' <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, an economist for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>, noted that new claims for unemployment compensation rose slightly last month, an indication of increased layoffs in some areas. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> believes there is still room for the jobless rate to fall over the next several months, `` but not in August.''
</TEXT>
