<HEAD>Economy Minister Resigns as Inflation Soars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s economy minister resigned Friday, three months after taking office, following a government report that showed inflation soared a record 243 percent during the first eight months of the year. President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> immediately appointed a new economy minister, <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, to fill the post vacated by <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Robles </PERSON>, the official gazette <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peruano </ORGANIZATION> said. Analysts said <PERSON> Robles </PERSON>' resignation was expected after disagreements arose in the Cabinet of Ministers over how to reactivate the nation's recession-ridden economy. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, current energy minister and former interior minister, was expected to move quickly to combat inflation with another round of austerity measures, analysts said. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrasco </PERSON>, a congressional deputy and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, is to head the energy ministry, the gazette said. <PERSON> Robles </PERSON>, the third economy minister in <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>'s center-left government, assumed his post just three months ago as a recession deepened and inflation skyrocketed. According to the government report, manufacturing has continued to decline, shortages of basic consumer products are widespread and the cost of living rose 30.9 percent in July, the highest single month total in Peruvian history. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said in a gazette communique Friday that August consumer prices increased 21.7 percent over the July level, and 243 percent from January through August. Independent analysts project inflation will pass 500 percent this year. The previous high mark was 158.3 percent in 1985. Inflation last year was 114.5 percent.
