<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-IndexFutures Bjt   09-02 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Index Futures, Bjt,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Index Futures, an American Invention, Debuts in Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Saturday in lead graf is correct.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Trading of stock-index futures began Saturday in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, theoretically giving investors a new opportunity to protect themselves if and when the big rally in the world's largest securities market ends. Although stock-index futures have been blamed by some critics for playing a significant role in the October stock market crash in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, there seems to be little concern the same thing could happen here, partly because of what strategists called <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s penchant for caution. `` The Japanese are a very wise people,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, an Asian-Pacific futures specialist at <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scrimgeour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vickers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> `` They like to acclimatize themselves properly before doing anything. Going off the board is n't their way of life. Their way of life is to do all their homework very carefully and make sure it works.'' A distinctly American financial invention that the Japanese have been eying for years, stock index futures are obligations to buy or sell the equivalent cash value of a group of stocks at a set price on a set date. Purchased for only a small fraction of their total worth, index futures theoretically enable investors to bet on the overall direction of the stock market. Index futures can serve as hedging mechanisms against a market drop or an inexpensive way to speculate on a market advance. Their eagerly awaited premiere in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> comes at a particularly opportune time, because <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> stock prices have been trading near their record highs. There has been increasing concern over how long the rally will last, and investors have been looking for ways to protect themselves in a decline. The debut of index futures in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> also coincides with simmering controversy in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on the impact of such financial strategies. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> critics say index futures encourage reckless speculation and conflict with the kind of long-term investing in individual stocks that is essential for healthy markets. Moreover, the critics contend, the development of high-speed computerized trading of index futures and the stocks that comprise them in order to profit from price differences, a technique called index arbitrage, has injected frightening volatility into the markets and discouraged would-be investors. Some studies have blamed index arbitrage for aggravating the Oct. 19 collapse of stock prices in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading, the most popular index futures are based on the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500-stock index, and the Major Market Index, a measurement of 20 stocks that closely tracks the more widely known Dow Jones Industrial Average. The Japanese concocted their index futures based on the Nikkei Index of 225 Selected Issues, which began trading Saturday on the <ORGANIZATION> Osaka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Price </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Index </ORGANIZATION>, called <ORGANIZATION> Topix </ORGANIZATION>, which began trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Japanese market professionals said trading began slowly, reflecting an underlying cautious approach. They said it would probably take a few years for the Japanese to develop profitable index arbitrage computerized strategies, and in the meantime the impact on stock prices likely would be small. Part of the problem in developing such strategies, they said, is that some stocks represented in the Nikkei or Topix indexes can not be traded via computer, which makes complicated arbitrage strategies difficult. In addition, Japanese stock markets are protected from wild swings by the daily limits placed on individual shares, another potential obstacle to profitable arbitrage between stocks and index futures. Both the Nikkei and <ORGANIZATION> Topix </ORGANIZATION> contracts will have a limit of 3 percent for a single day of trade, although if the market is orderly then exchange officials have the power to allow continued trading. `` Of course when volume builds up over time, the futures will become another factor affecting stocks,'' said a futures trader at <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> office, who asked not to be identified by name. `` But I do n't think there will be all that much speculative interest.''
</TEXT>
