<HEAD>Minnetonka Corp. Invests Fortune In Sequel To Obsession Perfume</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For <ORGANIZATION> Minnetonka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, there may be only one `` Obsession.'' But now the company hopes to extend its success in the personal fragrance business into `` Eternity.'' <LOCATION> Minnetonka </LOCATION> is spending about $ 18 million to launch Eternity, another <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> fragrance that the company says will appeal to a growing set of Americans interested in true romance and lasting love. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, founder and chairman of Bloomington-based <ORGANIZATION> Minnetonka </ORGANIZATION>, said he expects the new, floral scent to be as popular as its steamier predecessor, Obsession. `` Obsession stands for the'60s and'70s of the sexual revolution. It's warm and sensual,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. `` I think Eternity stands for love, romance and commitment.'' Regardless of the values they espouse, both perfumes have the smell of money. Obsession is the sales leader at <ORGANIZATION> Calvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cosmetics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the subsidiary that accounted for an estimated $ 105 million of <LOCATION> Minnetonka </LOCATION>'s 1987 sales of $ 152.4 million, said <PERSON> Marsha </PERSON> <PERSON> Raley </PERSON>, a stock analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Dain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bosworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. `` We think Eternity will be as big as Obsession,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. Largely on the continued strength of Obsession sales, <LOCATION> Minnetonka </LOCATION> is expected to record net income in 1988 of about $ 15.5 million, or 95 cents a share, <PERSON> Raley </PERSON> said. That compares with net income of $ 10.1 million, or 57 cents a share, in 1987, not counting the after-tax gain of $ 65 million on the sale of Softsoap to <ORGANIZATION> Colgate-Palmolive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` They're very creative,'' <PERSON> Raley </PERSON> said. `` They're good at identifying mass psychology trends. `` If you read the public right and you simplify what the public wants and you color it the way you think they want it colored then you end up striking a successful chord,'' <PERSON> Raley </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Delsing </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Calvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cosmetics </ORGANIZATION>, credit the fashion designer for attaching significance to Eternity. <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> is settling down after undergoing treatment for an addiction to vodka and valium and his life mirrors the message of Eternity, <PERSON> Delsing </PERSON> said. In fact, the fragrance got its name from an inscription on a ring purchased by <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> about a year ago for his wife. He bought the ring from a Duke of <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION> collection. `` Everything about Eternity so epitomizes his new lifestyle,'' <PERSON> Delsing </PERSON> said. But Eternity was n't designed in `` random creative'' fashion, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. Instead, <LOCATION> Minnetonka </LOCATION> identified a niche in the perfume market opposite Obsession and screened the samples that <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> chose from. `` It's more of a directed creative approach,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. `` We did n't want to cannibalize Obsession.'' <LOCATION> Minnetonka </LOCATION> has hopes that both fragrances will prove to be classics. Channel No. 5, for instance, has survived for 65 years. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, whose company acquired <ORGANIZATION> Calvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cosmetics </ORGANIZATION> in 1981, said he'll keep Obsession and Eternity alive by restricting distribution to about 700 stores. At $ 185 an ounce _ $ 10 more than Obsession _ Eternity is decidedly upscale and gets prime display space, he said. `` We do n't do anything unless it's prime,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. Eternity made its debut from June through August at two <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> stores in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Its national launch officially began this week, but <PERSON> Dayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> department stores have been selling it since the first weekend in August, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, a senior buyer of fine fragrances for Minneapolis-based <PERSON> Dayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> `` It's been tremendously successful,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said. `` We had customers literally grabbing four or five bottles off the first cart as it was being unpacked.'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said Eternity has been his company's chief focus for the past year. Next year an Eternity for men will be developed and <ORGANIZATION> Calvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cosmetics </ORGANIZATION> will introduce a line of dressing accessories such as belts, purses and cosmetic bags. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> continues to hold about 12 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Minnetonka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock, which has been selling in the range of $ 16 a share. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> has no intention of seeking a controlling interest in the company.
