d for local use. For instance, <PERSON> Beindorff </PERSON> said one local ad will show three players from a team with a tiger, a bear or some other team symbol. As the camera pans over them, the announcer will say `` three out of four -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Bengals </ORGANIZATION> or Bears or whatever -RRB- prefer'' Diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Digest </ORGANIZATION>, a trade publication based in <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, said soft drink sales rose about 4 percent last year to $ 40 billion, but that the diet segment has been growing four to five times faster. His 1987 beverage rankings listed Diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> as the third best selling soft drink behind Coca-Cola Classic and <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> with 7.7 percent of the market, and <ORGANIZATION> Diet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> fourth with 4.8 percent. <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> gives <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> `` high marks for clearly identifying the male image'' with its ads that featured <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON>, who defended his heavyweight title and said <PERSON> Diet </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepsi </PERSON> did too in taste tests against Diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Beindorff </PERSON> said the new diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> ads were in development long before the Tyson ads ran. While he would not disclose how much they cost, he said the fees for all the football players will come to only a fraction of the $ 1.25 million he said <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> reportedly paid <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON>.
