 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will recall 18,000 1984 Tempo and <PERSON> Topaz </PERSON> cars and spend up to $ 8.1 million on anti-smog repairs to meet <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> emissions standards, the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. In a news release, the regulatory board said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> will be sending notices through October to owners of 1984 Tempo and Topaz models sold in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> with 2.3 liter engines, offering free repairs. Dealerships will adjust air injection systems and install larger catalytic converters, at a cost to the manufacturer of about $ 450 a vehicle. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said that in tests of vehicles driven by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> motorists, the cars exceeded allowable limits of smog-forming hydrocarbons and oxides of nitrogen and emitted more than twice the allowable amount of carbon dioxide. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and federal regulations require cars to meet emissions standards for five years or 50,000 miles, and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> law requires manufacturers to repair emissions control system defects free during that period.
