<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1754EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     09-02 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repeating For All Needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bond Market Posts Biggest Gain Of Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Buisiness Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond market posted its biggest gain of the year and interest rates tumbled Friday as a new report on employment in August indicated the pace of economic growth may be slowing. The report defused concerns, at least for the time being, that the economy may be growing so fast that it could ignite inflation, which eats away at the value of fixed-income investments such as <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> notes and bonds. Slower growth is a plus for bond prices because credit demands and price pressures are usually lower in such periods and interest rates can fall. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, climbed 12.24 points to 1,142.50. That was the biggest rise since a 15.00-point advance on Oct. 22, 1987 when the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> was standing ready to provide liquidity to the financial system in the wake of the stock market crash. The biggest rise in the composite index this year had previously been a 12.05-point increase on Jan. 15. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s 30-year bond climbed nearly 2 | points, or about $ 26 for every $ 1,000 in face amount That was slightly below the $ 26.25 rise on Jan. 15, when the market was cheered by a narrowing of the nation's trade deficit. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from its price, skidded to 9.04 percent from 9.30 percent late Thursday. That was its lowest since it finished at 9.03 percent on Aug. 4. The bond rally was sparked by the government's report that the nation's unemployment rate rose to 5.6 percent in August from 5.4 percent in July. A companion report on business payrolls said there were 219,000 new jobs in August, and revised downward the payroll growth previously reported for July. In addition, the report indicated a decline in hours worked and only a slight increase in average hourly earnings index for August. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of money market research for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the report `` allays the market's fears that the economy was moving into an overheated phase. He said the pace of trading was moderate, a pickup from the slow pace that has preceded release of the report. <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, director of fixed-income research at <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` It was one of the most broadly-based, good reports we have seen in a long time.'' <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> <PERSON> Won </PERSON> <PERSON> Sohn </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Norwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, said the report means `` there is virtually no chance that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will tighten in the near future'' since the economy appears weaker than some presumed it was. <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said the report may mark a turning point for trends in longterm rates, but <PERSON> Sohn </PERSON> said he expects rates will head higher later this year. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, prices of short-term government issues rose by between -LCB- point and -RCB- point, intermediate maturities were up by between a full point and 1 -LCB- points and 20-year issues were up 2 -LCB- points, according to <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial information service. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. In corporate trading, prices rose. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 3.34 to 287.76. Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, meanwhile, fell to 7.42 percent as the discount fell 8 basis points to 7.20 percent. Yields on six-month bills fell to 7.78 percent as the discount fell 8 basis points to 7.40 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 8.04 percent as the discount fell 16 basis points to 7.50 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face value, which is paid at maturity. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted at 8 3-16 percent, down from 8 \ percent late Thursday
