<HEAD>Big Board Reallocates Four Stocks in Disciplinary Move</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that it has removed the rights of two specialist firms to make markets in four stocks following inquiries into their conduct during the October crash and its aftermath. The disciplinary move by the nation's biggest stock market against the firms, <ORGANIZATION> Stern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and Spear, <ORGANIZATION> Leeds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON>, brought to 11 the number of stocks that have been reallocated from <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> specialists because of probes into how well they handled the panicky buying and selling during the crash. In the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> system for stock trading, 54 specialist firms control the rights to market certain stocks and are required to keep order by setting opening prices and covering trades using their own money when there are too few buyers or sellers. Specialist monopoly rights on stocks are considered extremely valuable because the firms get the great majority of business in those stocks. Removal of those rights by the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> is considered a significant punitive measure. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> said after the crash that it would investigate several cases in which the specialists failed to maintain orderly trading in stocks they controlled. <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamsin </PERSON> said the announcement Friday marked the conclusion of those investigations. As is <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> policy, she declined to elaborate on what the specialists did or failed to do. But she reiterated the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZ