<HEAD>California Says Market Merger Would Cost Consumers Millions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AM-Lucky-American listed on the digest</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The purchase of Lucky markets by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> should be stopped because it would cost <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> consumers millions of dollars a year in higher food prices, the state attorney general said Friday. Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> filed suit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here late Thursday, seeking to block the $ 2.5 billion purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, which runs the supermarket Alpha Beta. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said a merger of the two companies would violate state antitrust laws. The deal, and the unrelated purchase of 172 Safeway stores in southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>, had been approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which analyzes the effect of business combinations on competition and prices. But <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON>, standing in an alley beside one of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION>'s Alpha Beta markets in the predominantly Hispanic <LOCATION> Westlake </LOCATION> district, accused the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> of failing to protect the interests of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> consumers `` This injustice will strike most cruelly at those least able to afford it _ the poor, the elderly, the least mobile of our citizens, those who can not afford high prices and who can not flee their neighborhood market for distant lower prices,'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said. American has said the deal would result in lower prices because of the efficiency of a larger operation. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> sought a temporary court order blocking the American-Lucky combination until a trial, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> delayed a decision until Tuesday so he could study the case. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON>'s staff continued to negotiate with <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> on a settlement of similar allegations about the El Monte-based grocery chain's $ 408 million purchase of 172 Safeway stores in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> already has started converting the stores. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said the talks appeared to be making progress, but warned he would take <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> to court immediately if the negotiations broke down. American, which recently moved its corporate headquarters from <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, is one of the nation's largest supermarket companies. Its holdings include Acme markets on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Skaggs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION> and Buttery in the West and the 27-state <LOCATION> Osco </LOCATION> drug chain. The transactions would give the combined <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta-Lucky </ORGANIZATION> chain 550 stores and <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> 350 stores, with the two chains together owning half the supermarkets in the state. In opposing the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> mergers, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> cited a study commissioned by his office that found the combination of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION> with Lucky and the Safeway-Vons deal would increase food prices by $ 400 million a year in the state As a condition of its approval, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> required <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> to sell 37 markets to competing chains to maintain competition. <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> was required to sell 12 stores.
