<HEAD>WPPSS Board OKs Lawsuit Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>'s executive board on Friday approved a settlement removing <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> from a securities fraud case that goes to trial next week in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION> The board met in private for an hour and then approved the settlement in a brief public meeting. The fraud lawsuit is the result of the 1983 default by <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> on $ 2.25 billion worth of bonds sold to begin construction on two nuclear power plants in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. The plants were abandoned, only partially complete, in 1982. Removal of <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> from the case leaves 21 <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> utilities, three engineering firms and a financial advisory firm as defendants. Trial is scheduled to begin Wednesday in federal court. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Foleen </PERSON>, a member of the executive board, said <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>' settlement could be the first step in settling all remaining bondholder claims `` It's my belief it is in the best interest of the ratepayers of the region that we get this matter settled,'' he said. `` I hope the supply system's action will be a positive element in the region and become a catalyst for further reasonable settlement.'' By leaving the case, the supply system will save millions of dollars in legal costs. It already has spent more than $ 23 million over five years to get to trial, and had budgeted $ 7 million more for a year of trial. Much of <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>' trial-cost savings, however, are expected to be picked up by remaining defendants.
